(3 comments)

This needs some more changes.

According to your definitions, DAL is an interface to interact with persistent storage backend (that sounds more like Image data stores).

1. Registry does not talk to them.

2. DAL and glance_store are equivalent

3. Glance API or Glance registry, both can talk to DB

4. glance_store also perform AuthN/AuthZ

5. Glance API does not perform AuthN, token is passed in from the user. It only does AuthZ.

6.Let's avoid glanceclient related information in this architecture. The client is an alternate way to talk to the REST API."}, {'account_id': 2537, 'date': '2015-03-10 19:30:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

Nikhil, we get DAL as Data Access Layer from official Sahara documentation where it means layer between server and DB. http://docs.openstack.org/developer/sahara/architecture.html

Wikipedia says that this is "A data access layer (DAL) in computer software, is a layer of a computer program which provides simplified access to data stored in persistent storage of some kind, such as an entity-relational database."

I agree with you that it's not a fully correct term so we decided to change it to "Database abstraction layer" which is surprisingly DAL too, and means "A database abstraction layer is an application programming interface which unifies the communication between a computer application and databases" (c) wikipedia.

Your remaining comments were also taken into account.'}, {'account_id': 11391, 'date': '2015-03-11 18:05:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

commit_message:
Refactor '_get_default_network' method in the integration tests

Refactored '_get_default_network' to get any network by its name,
othewise it was impossible to get 'public' net.

Change-Id: Ie691f99961a28e47f7437f3e52be9baf2984e839

commit_message:
Add multiattach capabilities injection

This patch is a follow up to the multiattach patch that adds
the ability to the scheduler to be able to filter capabilities
on the volume multiattach flag.   When a volume creation request
comes in with the multiattach flag set on a volume, there was no
way to filter out backends that don't support attaching a volume
to more than one host.   By defaut, no host supports it.  When
The Nova side lands, we can adjust drivers to add the new
multiattach:True capability reporting.

Change-Id: Ia426a2bf2ab8214f52fb6e70a3a1deff68d13d98

(2 comments)

sahid: please see the approved spec for these changes:
https://review.openstack.org/138444

The concerns for very large deployments are addressed in a config option added in the third patch in this series, when the actual calls from the scheduler to get instance information are implemented. If the overhead is too high, an operator can turn off this behavior entirely, and the scheduler will continue to make direct DB calls as it currently does.'}, {'account_id': 7730, 'date': '2015-03-04 14:27:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

(1 comment)

This looks for me not scalable and can make a terrible lock to the table instance needed by several other pieces of code but if the spec and this implementation was approved i guess it is ok.

Can you see my suggestion to make your algorithm better?'}, {'account_id': 1063, 'date': '2015-03-04 14:45:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

(1 comment)

sahid: the original version of the spec didn't have the HostManager get all the instances at once; instead, it got all the compute nodes, and then iterated through them, getting the instances for each host. That was felt to be even heavier, since it would involve multiple calls to the DB. The current design, getting all the instances in one call, was a direct suggestion from core reviewers."}, {'account_id': 7730, 'date': '2015-03-04 15:40:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

(1 comment)

(1 comment)

commit_message:
Add InstanceList.get_all method

As part of the effort to remove direct DB calls from the Scheduler
filters, there needs to be a method for getting an InstanceList object
containing all the instances available.

Partially-Implements: blueprint isolate-scheduler-db
(https://blueprints.launchpad.net/nova/+spec/isolate-scheduler-db)

Change-Id: Ie5e0e4f2dbb46da5df91067cfe90de366fc9adc9

    package installer file for datastores in

    in a pkgs directory in user's home.

  for datastore: <DATASTORE_NAME>"

  Vertica package from https://my.vertica.com and place
  the file at DATASTORE_PKG_LOCATION.

if package file-name is vertica.deb and it is placed in /tmp,
then to run kick-start proceed as follows:

  $ export DATASTORE_PKG_LOCATION=/tmp/vertica.deb
  $ ./redstack kick-start vertica

commit_message:
Create DIB elements for HP Vertica on Ubuntu

A specification for this change was submitted for review in
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/151126/

Changes:
- Creates the disk-image-builder elements for
  installing HP Vertica on Ubuntu.

- Introduces new env variables DATASTORE_PKG_LOCATION which
  specifies location to look for package installer file.

- It would be the job of elements(extra-data.d) to discover
  existence of DATASTORE_PKG_LOCATION, and notify appropriate
  error message in case of non-existent DATASTORE_PKG_LOCATION.

To execute kick-start for Vertica, user has to download
Vertica package from https://my.vertica.com and place
file at DATASTORE_PKG_LOCATION and update the value of
DATASTORE_PKG_LOCATION to point to actual package-file.

For eg.
if package file-name is vertica.deb and it is placed in /tmp,
then to run kick-start proceed as follows:

  $ export DATASTORE_PKG_LOCATION=/tmp/vertica.deb
  $ ./redstack kick-start vertica

Partially Implements: blueprint vertica-db-support

Change-Id: Ibc64b42eb5d2f4722eb27a7bc730dda98014347f

commit_message:
Restructure the in-memory node usage

Instead of retaining full paths only retain
partial paths; this then allows for finding
a parent node and then easily finding a child
by using the find() routines.

This more naturally emulates a real filesystem
using our tree structure and simplifies certain
operations to make them more efficient/simple.

Change-Id: I207b02c979704a15eac8be46d11a0af61b05d9b9

you may have a check on /usr/local/lib/liberasurecode.*, should be be 1.0.4'}, {'account_id': 7485, 'date': '2015-03-12 11:53:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Hi Clay, you probably already have this figured out, but the pypi version builds/installs the integrated liberasurecode version, only if not already installed.  Given it was a temporary solution to integrate liberasurecode with pyeclib, we didn't add a version check to the mix, which we probably should now, that we have encountered this.  Our assumption was that folks have been using pyeclib-0.9.8 which didn't require liberasurecode at all (and thus wasn't installed).  FWIW, we'll get the version check added to pyeclib.

In short, as Yuan already pointed out, you will need liberasurecode tag v1.0.1 or greater, which you can get by installing it directly from https://tsg-@bitbucket.org/tsg-/liberasurecode.git, OR get rid of your current liberasurecode so's and then pip reinstall pyeclib, which will automagically update liberasurecode for you.  :)"}, {'account_id': 7485, 'date': '2015-03-12 12:39:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Just double checked pyeclib installer script and it does already check to make sure the liberasurecode version is correct (by virtue of using the full soname to check the presence of the library).  So Clay if you are still seeing issues, can you please run pyeclib unit tests on the latest pyeclib master (nosetests) and report the outcome.'}, {'account_id': 7847, 'date': '2015-03-12 14:13:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+2

lrwxrwxrwx 1 root root 23 Mar 12 13:40 /usr/local/lib/liberasurecode.so -> liberasurecode.so.1.0.4*

# test_storage_policy.py barfed

% sudo ldconfig

nosetests test/unit -x
# all pass :)"}, {'account_id': 7847, 'date': '2015-03-12 15:22:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Also, to get tox -e py27 to pass I had to manually fix requirements.txt to have pyeclib>=1.0.3 and then 

tox -r -e py27

commit_message:
Bring EC API calls in sync with PyECLib 1.0

Changes in PyECLib 1.0:

  * All PyECLib exceptions consolidated into one (ECDriverError)
    with improved error handling
  * Uses liberasurecode-provided EC backends
    (some semantic/error reporting changes)
  * EC backend names brought in sync with liberasurecode
    (flat_xor_3 -> flat_xor_hd_3,
     flat_xor_4 -> flat_xor_hd_4,
     jerasure_rs_cauchy_orig -> jerasure_rs_cauchy)

Change-Id: I941541f8043c8a4851815df654e467d42f00c357

(1 comment)

I like the proposal but unfortunately it solves only part of the problem because hypervisor_hostname is not unique in the VMware case (see bug 1329261). There was an attempt to fix that by using a combination of vCenter UUID + cluster_name as hypervisor_hostname but it was rejected because it was not considered a 'real' hostname.

If we are going to introduce DB schema changes, I really wish to go for a complete solution that will fix both 1329261 and 1419785. What about renaming 'hypervisor_hostname' to 'hypervisor_id' and making it unique?"}, {'account_id': 9555, 'date': '2015-02-25 14:33:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

As for renaming hypervisor_hostname to hypervisor_id, I fully support that. I don't want to do it in this change, though, because nobody's currently talking about the colour of that bikeshed, and it's not strictly required."}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2015-02-25 16:59:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

not too keen on this, I would prefer the driver specific solution. The fact that drivers want to run 'HA' nova-computes, means we have much deeper issues."}, {'account_id': 9555, 'date': '2015-02-26 21:35:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Joe, that's really orthogonal to this issue. It is possible to hit this bug by fat fingering during a non-HA deployment. As I mentioned on the ML, this bug arises because nova compute can't be co-located with the hypervisor, and that's fundamental to both VMware and Ironic."}, {'account_id': 9555, 'date': '2015-02-26 21:36:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

so -1, until we get some ironic feedback"}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2015-02-26 23:04:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Correct me if I'm wrong, but this doesn't actually solve the problem of running this code if the hostname changes, right? Like, I think you can hit this if you start up a compute node, create an instance, then change the hostname of that compute node and restart. You hit the same problem, right?

The more concerning thing to me, is that if we enforce this UC, don't we now effectively make it impossible to move the compute service from one $hostA to another $hostB and manage the same node? Without hacking the database, that is... It would be extremely mean to put this in place and have someone with a vmware or ironic _compute_ failure suddenly unable to start the service on another $hostB because $compute_node is already in the database with $hostA. Granted, the fallout right now is also bad, but if we're going to enforce it to the point of _not_starting_ we should at least have a managed way to update the linkage in the database. However, that leads me to feel that this is far too strict of a requirement. Wouldn't it be much more flexible if we let the hypervisor being managed decide if it's being managed doubly instead of us guessing without even considering the up/down/whatever state of the running services?"}, {'account_id': 9555, 'date': '2015-02-26 23:39:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@Joe I don't see this as a workaround at all. I believe this patch fixes the database schema to correctly model current assumptions in the code.

However, even if we want to treat it as a workaround, I'd point out that it's currently the only workaround to this problem. As I pointed out in comments, Dan's patch is never going to prevent anybody from losing their data if they hit this, because they won't have switched it on. As developers, we can't even agree who should switch it on. On top of that, nothing else currently proposed will prevent the multitude of more subtle bugs caused by the same issue.

Discussions about fixing evacuate more thoroughly in L, or whether to better support multi-node compute aside, this change:

* is correct
* is the only robust fix available for a severe data loss bug
* does not preclude further fixes in the future
* accurately models usage, so seems unlikely to be reverted in any case

Is there a good reason not to merge this patch?"}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2015-03-06 21:25:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

"is correct"

-- It appears correct yes, but if we get this wrong its really bad. So I am uncomfortable with a db migration like this so late in the cycle.

"is the only robust fix available for a severe data loss bug"

-- I think its very reasonable to ask operators to look over the new config file on every upgrade. When I was an operator I did that.

"does not preclude further fixes in the future"

 -- Perhaps, but undoing a DB migration is not something we want to do.

"accurately models usage, so seems unlikely to be reverted in any case"

-- Honestly I don't know. If we didn't have any clustered hypervisors I would agree with you. But we do, and they don't integrate will into nova today, so I can see us looking into changing  a lot of things.'}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2015-03-06 22:57:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

> - is correct
> - accurately models usage, so seems unlikely to be reverted in any case

I've been thinking about this quite a bit the last few days, and I don't think that either of these statements are correct. I believe that it solves a particular problem in an easy way, but I don't think that it's accurately changing the database to model reality.

With our current model, and with the model proposed in this patch, we can technically insert into the database a pair of records that indicate that a single host is managing two hypervisors. This could happen if I were to start two instances of nova-compute on my compute host to, say, manage KVM and Xen. Both would create their records, which would lead us to having this in the database: (host1, hypervisor1) and (host1,  hypervisor2). They'd both bind to the compute.host1 topic, and the API service would send messages destined for action on instances claiming to be on host1 down that topic, at extreme peril. Clearly this is broken currently, and it's loosened (conceptually) by this patch which seems to imply that the only thing we need to be unique about is who is managing a given hypervisor node at any given time.

The naive fix to this would be to extend this change to break apart the unique(host, hypervisor) constraint into two, one unique(host) and one unique(hypervisor). That would prevent multiple compute services from starting up claiming to be the same host. However, as I understand it, this would immediately break Ironic, which legitimately (given our current model, such it is) creates multiple records for a given host, because of the node concept. Thus, we end up correctly with (host1, ironicnode1), (host1, ironicnode2), etc in the database, which wouldn't be allowed if we had a unique constraint on hostname.

So, granted that our current model doesn't fully reflect reality either, I think it's a closer suggestion of what we expect, which is that a single compute host manages one or more hypervisor nodes, even though it doesn't actually prevent the case where we have multiple compute services started by accident. It is, I think, an example of why the host,node "model" inside nova continues to plague us, and why many of us really want it to go away.

Thus, I think we need to (again) have a deeper conversation about what nova's model is (and isn't) and how we're going to continue to support the drivers we currently have without making things worse. Clearly Ironic and vmware are pegs that don't fit very well, but are also differently-shaped pegs. For the time being, I'd still prefer to see the immediate vmware problem solved inside the driver, and for the evacuate cleanup logic fixed so that the penalty for a misconfiguration is less severe.'}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2015-03-07 22:57:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

For the time being, I'd still prefer to see the immediate vmware problem solved inside the driver, and for the evacuate cleanup logic fixed so that the penalty for a misconfiguration is less severe."

As would I.

Best,

> I've been thinking about this quite a bit the last few days, and I don't think that either of these statements are correct. I believe that it solves a particular problem in an easy way, but I don't think that it's accurately changing the database to model reality.
> With our current model, and with the model proposed in this patch, we can technically insert into the database a pair of records that indicate that a single host is managing two hypervisors. This could happen if I were to start two instances of nova-compute on my compute host to, say, manage KVM and Xen. Both would create their records, which would lead us to having this in the database: (host1, hypervisor1) and (host1, hypervisor2). They'd both bind to the compute.host1 topic, and the API service would send messages destined for action on instances claiming to be on host1 down that topic, at extreme peril. Clearly this is broken currently, and it's loosened (conceptually) by this patch which seems to imply that the only thing we need to be unique about is who is managing a given hypervisor node at any given time.
> The naive fix to this would be to extend this change to break apart the unique(host, hypervisor) constraint into two, one unique(host) and one unique(hypervisor). That would prevent multiple compute services from starting up claiming to be the same host. However, as I understand it, this would immediately break Ironic, which legitimately (given our current model, such it is) creates multiple records for a given host, because of the node concept. Thus, we end up correctly with (host1, ironicnode1), (host1, ironicnode2), etc in the database, which wouldn't be allowed if we had a unique constraint on hostname.

No, you can't currently put a unique constraint on host, as that would prevent both the VMware and Ironic drivers from controlling multiple hypervisors. There was discussion of the VMware driver removing this, but it hasn't happened (this is an unrelated rabbit hole!).

There may be a solution to the problem you describe of a user attempting to configure 2 different hypervisors which use different drivers on the same host. However, think for a moment about how likely that is. Who is ever going to do that accidentally? Now compare this to the possibility of somebody standing up a second Nova compute for a second VMware instance, and accidentally entering the hostname of the first VMware instance.

Lets be pragmatic, here. I think this is a good solution which will last. However, even if it's not, it's still a good solution which fixes an immediate problem, and doesn't break any existing functionality. You can't say that about any other patch proposed for this issue.

> So, granted that our current model doesn't fully reflect reality either, I think it's a closer suggestion of what we expect, which is that a single compute host manages one or more hypervisor nodes, even though it doesn't actually prevent the case where we have multiple compute services started by accident. It is, I think, an example of why the host,node "model" inside nova continues to plague us, and why many of us really want it to go away.
Thus, I think we need to (again) have a deeper conversation about what nova's model is (and isn't) and how we're going to continue to support the drivers we currently have without making things worse. Clearly Ironic and vmware are pegs that don't fit very well, but are also differently-shaped pegs. For the time being, I'd still prefer to see the immediate vmware problem solved inside the driver, and for the evacuate cleanup logic fixed so that the penalty for a misconfiguration is less severe.

This is a VMware and Ironic problem, and potentially a problem in other drivers. I do not preclude further changes, but I still haven't seen any reason not to proceed with this one. It is the only proposed solution which prevents a severe data loss bug. I don't claim that it fixes all severe data loss bugs, but 1 is a good start.'}, {'account_id': 9555, 'date': '2015-03-12 21:47:20.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Fucked if I know why.'}]

commit_message:
Ensure a hypervisor is only managed by a single compute host

Nova does not support a hypervisor managed by more than 1 compute
host. This change makes that lack of support explicit by causing Nova
to raise an exception when attempting to create a compute node which
violates it. If the compute driver reports all nodes at startup, as
the VMware driver does, and Ironic can do, this will cause a
misconfigured Nova to fail to start. This is preferrable to allowing
the system to run, which will require manual cleanup and may result in
data loss.

Specifically, if the compute driver reports a hypervisor node from
get_available_nodes(), Nova assumes that all instances associated with
that node will also have the same compute host. This assumption is
pervasive, and violating it breaks a large number of things. The bug
below notes that the evacuation cleanup code will cause all instances
running on the hypervisor to be erroneously deleted. It will also
prevent all periodic tasks from running correctly.

There are currently only 2 drivers which report a hypervisor identity
different to the compute host: VMware and Ironic. No other drivers
are affected by this change.

Note that this change is not related to support for multiple
hypervisors per compute host. It relates to a single hypervisor being
accidentally managed by multiple compute hosts, which is not
supported.

Closes-Bug: #1419785
Change-Id: I48c2331e66532cd043da8aecdb8e7649776e836a

commit_message:
Log stdout from build_wheels in cache_devstack

This commit adds a print statement with the stdout from the run_local()
call which executes build_wheels.sh in devstack. Right now when the
script is executed all it does is print that it's running but we are
unable to debug anything that could potentially go wrong during the
execution of the script without the output from build_wheels.

Change-Id: I7433f054127a42fa73598db219c6e351efc98fb7

commit_message:
Update latest modules from oslo-incubator

Updates the _i18n, versionutils, and install_venv_common
modules to the latest from oslo-incubator. The other modules
listed in openstack-common.conf (lockutils, log, importlib, and
fixture) could not be found because they are not part of
oslo-incubator anymore. The log module was updated by hand to
fix a bug, but it and the other deprecated modules should be
replaced with the appropriate substitutions.

Change-Id: I14a7a31e7208a9dc5dbd5686fbeab824b455ffa8
Partial-Bug: 1430124

commit_message:
Make dependency on boto entirely conditional

By moving the import into the (only) method that needs boto.exception we
retain the ability to list the options from that driver without breaking
glance_store.backend.register_opts.

Closes-bug: 1426767
Change-Id: Ie35b4b41f71b79502cb2d4b83c2037ec0d798557

we need this file to be loaded to gain access to the config options.

commit_message:
Temporary fix for being able to load neutron_lbaas.conf

This bug prevents neutron_lbaas.conf from being loaded and
we need this file to be loaded to gain access to the config options.
This is just a temporary solution and should immediately be undone
once a fix for the bug has been commited to neutron.
https://bugs.launchpad.net/neutron/+bug/1430153

Change-Id: Idcdd09006613b77847d8fc83c2225ad3b0540c13

commit_message:
Fix for broken languagepack logs command

We need to use the print_list() method to display results,
not the print_dict() method.

Change-Id: I25994a969445059cde48400218c7a3e5fe6a2eca
Closes-bug: 1431528

anymore in manila. So, remove it as duplication.

commit_message:
lazy loading for logbooks and flowdetails

You can now specify a "lazy" argument when asking a
persistence backend for a logbook for flowdetail.
This will return a logbook with no flowdetails in it,
or a flowdetail with no atomdetails in it, respectively.

Change-Id: Ie81a19a2107b44e2c35c2a92507bec03eee55c50

commit_message:
Move policy enforcement into REST API layer for v2.1 extended_volumes

This patch moves the policy enforcement into REST API layer for v2.1
extend_volumes extension and adds related unittest.

Partially implements bp v3-api-policy
DocImpact

Change-Id: Ib67e423aaf0d1878ebaa6d9a5304d1a757913dd5

commit_message:
Remove useless policy rules for v2.1 api which removed/disabled

Because V2.1 must be identical with V2 and must not contain any new
attributes and new method. So the swap/attach/deatch in extend_volume
was removed.  But there still left some policy rules related to it.
This patch cleanup them.

Change-Id: I6e7e3263261519f72fa6b067db6a5930026f02dd

commit_message:
Allow injected atom args to be persisted

Instead of only storing injected atom arguments in memory
allow for specifying those to be persisted; so that users
who desire this feature can persist them (it defaults to
being transient to retain the old API behavior).

This also reworks the validating of engine dependencies
to be more correct. It removes the validation of these
dependencies from the prepare() method and moves them to a
new engine validate() method; this allows users to prepare()
the engine, then inject there atom non-transient arguments
and then validate(); the validation would fail prior to this
at preparation time since no injected arguments would
exist and the user would not have the ability to inject any
that target a specific atom, since the atom detail would
not have been created yet (since that is populated in the
prepartion method).

Change-Id: I2846d0334db32a115592f850d85b206d9e6a3f07

commit_message:
Allow backend connection config (via fetch) to be a string

To make it easier to provide just a connection string to the
persistence backend fetch mechanism (without needing to create
a dictionary with just a 'connection' key) match the behavior
of the other fetch-like functions and accept a string to
simplify the interaction with this function.

Change-Id: I59cd330c545985fe9782c3049690425ead1c8cf3

commit_message:
Add boto to requirements.txt.

On exec glance-api displayed exception "ImportError: No module named boto.exception".

% /usr/bin/glance-api
2015-02-28 15:21:25.949 23107 ERROR stevedore.extension [-] Could not load 's3': No module named boto.exception
2015-02-28 15:21:25.950 23107 ERROR stevedore.extension [-] No module named boto.exception
2015-02-28 15:21:25.950 23107 TRACE stevedore.extension Traceback (most recent call last):
2015-02-28 15:21:25.950 23107 TRACE stevedore.extension   File "/usr/lib/python2.7/site-packages/stevedore/extension.py", line 162, in _load_plugins
2015-02-28 15:21:25.950 23107 TRACE stevedore.extension     verify_requirements,
2015-02-28 15:21:25.950 23107 TRACE stevedore.extension   File "/usr/lib/python2.7/site-packages/stevedore/extension.py", line 185, in _load_one_plugin
2015-02-28 15:21:25.950 23107 TRACE stevedore.extension     plugin = ep.load(require=verify_requirements)
2015-02-28 15:21:25.950 23107 TRACE stevedore.extension   File "/usr/lib/python2.7/site-packages/pkg_resources.py", line 2025, in load
2015-02-28 15:21:25.950 23107 TRACE stevedore.extension     entry = __import__(self.module_name, globals(),globals(), ['__name__'])
2015-02-28 15:21:25.950 23107 TRACE stevedore.extension   File "/usr/lib/python2.7/site-packages/glance_store/_drivers/s3.py", line 26, in <module>
2015-02-28 15:21:25.950 23107 TRACE stevedore.extension     import boto.exception
2015-02-28 15:21:25.950 23107 TRACE stevedore.extension ImportError: No module named boto.exception

boto does not exist to glance_store requirements.

After boto installation, issue was fixed.

Change-Id: Idc11d10e7ded41ef2b934f8c93df1e101828cd84
Closes-Bug: #1426767

commit_message:
Run nodepool-coverage as a check job

We are currently working to make nodepool much better tested. Add a
coverage job to the check queue so that we can see how we are doing as
we add new tests.

Change-Id: Ib47763b35b11d8f794bfa5352fdab449d7d7d66a

[{'created': '2015-03-02 23:58:57.000000000', 'message': 'Use ordered(set/dict) to retain ordering of requires/optional

Change-Id: I365d11bbba4aa221bc36ca15441acecf199b4d56
'}, {'created': '2015-03-03 01:13:31.000000000', 'message': 'Allow using ordered(set/dict) to retain ordering

Instead of using always using a set/dict which do not retain
ordering allow for atoms to override the dict and set types
to be other compatible types, such as a ordered set and a ordered
dict to be used for requires, optional, and provides and rebind
mappings types so that the ordering of these containers is
maintained later when they are used.

These ordering can be useful depending on the atom type (such
as in a map and reduce tasks). By default we just retain the
existing types, but allow for others to subclass and replace
them with compatible types as needed.

Partial-Bug: 1357117

Change-Id: I365d11bbba4aa221bc36ca15441acecf199b4d56

commit_message:
Use ordered[set/dict] to retain ordering

Instead of using always using a set/dict which do not retain
use a ordered set and a ordered dict for requires, optional,
and provides and rebind mappings types so that the ordering
of these containers is maintained later when they are used.

These ordering can be useful depending on the atom type (such
as in a map and reduce tasks).

Partial-Bug: 1357117

Change-Id: I365d11bbba4aa221bc36ca15441acecf199b4d56

commit_message:
Add support for identity_uri.

This patch adds the ability to set a new keystone_identity_uri
parameter.  It also deprecates the old keystone_host, keystone_port,
keystone_protocol, and keystone_auth_admin_prefix parameters. Logic
is in place so that users of the deprecated settings should have a
smooth upgrade process and get deprecation warnings until they adopt
the new settings.

Change-Id: Ideefb4d824cbd5b4b83f9eb773a75e536e3458fb

The Manila cDOT driver uses its own timing code called from
get_share_stats() to do ASUP logging.  The periodic ASUP task

commit_message:
Manila cDOT driver should use loopingcall for ASUP report timing

The Manila cDOT driver uses its own timing code called from
get_share_stats() to do ASUP logging.  The periodic ASUP task
should instead be controlled by an independent loopingcall task.
This simplifies the driver and better separates code paths that
are unrelated and should run separately.

Change-Id: Ia3deda9415ecb2c026d4e91d047c8611b8432674
Closes-Bug: #1429972

commit_message:
Don't add exception instance in LOG.exception

LOG.exception will print out the full stacktrace, that's enough.
We should only record meaningful message.

Change-Id: I8b5c581717e6b78c11c46e226463927450c9f287

Thomas I think what you are seeing is the clear need for some body in your commit message. You have a title, but you have no body to your commit message. Neither Jim nor myself said that having a group was wrong, we both just wanted to see that you knew why you were including it in the patch. Now yes you did reply to me, but unfortunately it is time consuming for a reviewer to have to go through every past comment to review a patch, I'm guessing I've spent 20 minutes going through the review history of the patch so I can write a clear comment to you.

I suggest taking a look at https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GitCommitMessages for a general overview.

Specifically I would recommend that you detail your intention for creating this patch and convey your knowledge of the process when you do so. Adding the sentence "This patch intentionally adds a group: bagpipe-l2 to gerrit/projects.yaml to map to the launchpad group: https://launchpad.net/bagpipe-l2

This informs reviewers of your motivation for doing what you are doing in your patch so they don't have to keep asking and comb the past patches for the answer.

And yes, you do need the group for the reasons you outlined.

Thanks Thomas,
Anita.'}, {'account_id': 6316, 'date': '2015-03-11 17:19:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Code-Review-1'}, {'account_id': 12021, 'date': '2015-03-12 09:01:24.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 9.'}, {'account_id': 12021, 'date': '2015-03-12 09:04:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

commit_message:
Add networking-bagpipe-l2 project

This stackforge project will host an ML2 mechanism driver relying on
bagpipe-bgp to implement Neutron networks with E-VPN.

Note that this patch intentionally adds a group 'bagpipe-l2' to
gerrit/projects.yaml, to map to the launchpad group at
https://launchpad.net/bagpipe-l2 .

Change-Id: Ib85f6247ae9ea2e29febe6cf39e7c2f224216159

[{'created': '2015-03-11 21:16:10.000000000', 'message': "Fix infinite recursion caused by unnecessary stub

The auth tests used a stub to alter `nova.RequestContext` to become
`FakeRequestContext`. The problem with this is that `FakeRequestContext`
inherits from `nova.RequestContext` which has the effect of making
`FakeRequestContext` point to itself for it's parent class.

This leads to infinite recursion if a context object is created after this
stub is set.

This code has worked up until now because no tests have created a new context
after this stub was set. Downstream patches, however, may end up creating a
context here, so we should fix this.

It turns out that this stub isn't necessary, so deleting it entirely is
sufficient to fix the issue and keep tests passing.

Closes-Bug: 1431022

commit_message:
Fix infinite recursion caused by unnecessary stub

The auth tests used a stub to alter `nova.RequestContext` to become
`FakeRequestContext`. The problem with this is that `FakeRequestContext`
inherits from `nova.RequestContext` which has the effect of making
`FakeRequestContext` point to itself for it's parent class.

This leads to infinite recursion if a context object is created after this
stub is set.

This code has worked up until now because no tests have created a new context
after this stub was set. Downstream patches, however, may end up creating a
context here, so we should fix this.

It turns out that this stub isn't necessary, so deleting it entirely is
sufficient to fix the issue and keep tests passing.

Closes-Bug: 1431022

Change-Id: I6969dc2759ff2dbb78de831dbd40ea24cc3840ad

@Joel, sorry to reply you late.

if I understand the patch correctly,
Yingjun wants to check if the `tenant_id` match project_id of the instance been attached.

In his patch, he does check in rest api[2] side, which means,  this check is been done by call additional neutron call(self.network_api.show_port(context, port_id)) to get the port information before doing attaching. 
I think this is kinds of overhead, since he did addition network_api call.

by checking the code in neutron api[1] in nova side, the allocate_for_instance() function in neutron api will get the port information (allocate_for_instance is called by self.compute_api.attach_interface(...) ), so my thinking is we can check the port information in neutron api code, and raise a exception in neutron api, then handle it in restapi[2] side.

for example:
you can add after line 372 in [1],

if port_info['port']['tenant_id'] != instance.project_id:
    raise some_Exception
...

and handle it in [2].


[1]https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/network/neutronv2/api.py#L372
[2]https://review.openstack.org/#/c/146788/8/nova/api/openstack/compute/plugins/v3/attach_interfaces.py

in my comments:
restapi : nova/api/openstack/compute/*
neutron api: nova/network/neutronv2/api.py

I am sorry , I am still -1 for my comments in PS7.
thanks,
Eli."}, {'account_id': 4428, 'date': '2015-02-10 07:26:36.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 9.'}, {'account_id': 4428, 'date': '2015-02-10 07:26:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

I believe the code should be returning a 4040 Not Found, not a 403 Forbidden. Please see inline for discussion.

commit_message:
Improve 'attach interface' exception handling

Previously, if a user attempted to launch an instance and specified a
port that belonged to a different tenant, a HTTP 500 Server
Error was returned to the user. This patch changes that to a
more informative HTTPBadRequest exception.

Change-Id: I4a4017407ac7358490974cbffc5b7dbb7a200f44
Closes-bug: #1409617

commit_message:
Create DesignateAdapter and surrounding infrastructure

This implements the basic infrastructure for DesignateAdapter
and creates the basis for the API v2/v1 Adapter objects

These will replace views in both the v1 and v2 APIs, and allow for the
validation of API requests to move into the DesignateObjects themselves.

Example use is

   zone = central.get_domain(blah)
   DesignateAdapter.render('API_v1', zone)
   // Returns v1 dict, ready to	convert to JSON

These objects have a registry of sorts, so all calls will be made to
DesignateAdapter, and the combination of the format param ('API_v1' in
this case) will load the right Adapter and return the right JSON ready
dict.

Change-Id: I2b77205751675de600248180fafbfe22a2c1d8f5
Blueprint: validation-cleanup

commit_message:
EMC Isilon Manila driver

The Isilon Manila driver supports the following functionalities:
* Create/delete NFS/CIFS share
* Create/delete snapshot
* Allow/deny access to share
* Create share from snapshot

implements: blueprint emc-isilon-manila-driver

Change-Id: If5f064751120890afba0571bc2b407d141ba0323

commit_message:
Fix return code of irc_tests.py

commit_message:
Language pack does not return source_uri during creation

After a language pack is created, the source uri is not displayed
by the CLI on create. Subsequent calls to show the language pack do.

Change-Id: Idc1f3f529fe8da4b99de743759ae1da3dc116596
Closes-bug: 1430927

(3 comments)

This change is wrong as is, marking as WIP for cleaning up.

The generated nova.conf.sample file contains:
[workarounds]

#
# Options defined in nova.utils
#

# This option allows a fallback to sudo for performance
# reasons. For example see
# https://bugs.launchpad.net/nova/+bug/1415106 (boolean value)
#disable_rootwrap=false

That's the value that needs to be documented - and it's a nova.conf value that is only relevant for Compute - not for Cinder, not for Neutron.

IMHO the bug is already solved with change 157181 which updates the generated options.

Mentioning it in  	
doc/admin-guide-cloud/compute/section_compute-rootwrap.xml
 would be ok as well (with a reference that this is a Kilo change)."}, {'account_id': 10897, 'date': '2015-02-23 03:35:40.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 10897, 'date': '2015-02-23 03:37:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Workflow-1

commit_message:
Add Information on Disabling Root Wrapper

Updating the Admin Guide and with the doc impact information from
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/150904/: If root wrapper performance
becomes deficient or inadequate, this configuration disables root wrapper,
and adds a sudo only fallback.

Change-Id: Id583a03f02dd2730b87588e9f9defd19739f719c
backport: none
Closes-Bug: #1415747

commit_message:
Add ro level of access support to generic driver

Recently was added funtionality of rw/ro level of access to API.
Implement its support with NFS protocol for Generic driver and raise
error for CIFS protocol if it is not rw, because it does not allow
to handle both - ro and rw access rules for IPs/nets using one share export.

Implements BP generic-driver-ro-access

Change-Id: Iec7c01790bade6d4ce2f50b5a691e563dd756aa5

commit_message:
NetApp cDOT driver should not create useless export-policy rule

When using manila with a cDOT backend, the 'manila create' command
creates an export-policy for every newly created NFS share and adds
a policy rule with "localhost".  This is not necessary.

Change-Id: If4b54255328ed7384a195609d7e4e99c79d10638
Closes-Bug: #1427791

commit_message:
Add keystone docker-compose file.

To follow the model of container sets, net will be set to
host so that containers will not need to be linked together.

All enviroment variables will come from 'openstack.env'.

Co-authored-by: Ian Main <imain@redhat.com>

Change-Id: Ifdb0f146ff82c0fedb09255f6e1955ecdc435444

commit_message:
Improve error handling in refactored Tgt driver

Only allow IOError to fall through when file not found is
acceptable. Cleanup a few error messages, remove uses of six as
this is not required

Closes-Bug: 1422095
Change-Id: I8a8f1ee561b15b38860b31cae1b444527e998869

commit_message:
provisioning rabbitmq via userdata/cloud-init

- changed create cluster flows from a combination of unordered and
  linear flows to a graph flow
- added userdata generation step to create userdata to be used by
  each VM
- added check_or_restart_rabbitmq, to check rabbitmq status a
  number of times then restart the VM, before checking again

Change-Id: I98f2aa031ccd7e8bb068fa4cece3dd8af263e33e

commit_message:
Add oneshot cron trigger

Add the possibility to launch oneshot cron triggers.
Those trigger are only executed once at a given date.

To use them you must specify a special pattern begining with an "@".
"@YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM"

Exemple:
mistral cron-trigger-create test "@2015-02-11 16:18" reboot_server input.json

Once executed, instead of computing the next occurence, the trigger is deleted.

Change-Id: I78f6c9d69fd610475c640074aa22c11a10f9c90f

and it contains numerous entities that are never used. This patch

commit_message:
Add Client object to documentation

After wanting to do a rather simple thing -- figure out of the
"timeout" argument to nodepool was a int or a float, it lead me down
the rabbit-hole to python-novaclient.

It turns out the timeout does get passed through to requests as a
float so that mystery was solved.

But the "Client" class seems to be missing from the documentation as
it's not included in the class list.  So add that and also at least
document the types of the arguments.

However, then I noticd that this wasn't showing up; turns out sphinx
requires "autoclass_content = both" if you want it to document
__init__() functions.  Several other classes had their init args
documented but they weren't showing up because of this.

Change-Id: I8f44e92f2a0f25a75926b1813a8b374e79b4f5db

Testing some things in devstack I find that cinder v1 accepts on display_name as the query parameter whereas cinder v2 accepts display_name and name.

I'm testing things because we have learned recently that the cli has magic to go call the cinder api directly, whereas the library volumes calls don't. And the library volumes calls use a wrong url (for the nova volumes proxy api)."}, {'account_id': 4690, 'date': '2015-03-11 23:06:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I'm trying to determine if this is the right way to fix the problem.

So far, I find this line is supposed to make find_resource go for display_name instead of name for volumes:

https://github.com/openstack/python-novaclient/blob/0a60aae/novaclient/v2/volumes.py#L30

But somehow that's not working. Looking further."}, {'account_id': 4690, 'date': '2015-03-11 23:56:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Okay, I found that commit 07260236ab2179579e0d0d2f9b7fb8027652dc32 made it so the query goes from display_name to name and now we're going to put display_name back.

Being that we lack functional tests, this is probably the safest way to fix it until we can add more testing and clean things up after.

I also checked that the nova volumes proxy api accepts both name and display_name, so this fix works in all cases (cinder v1, cinder v2, nova volumes proxy).

GET http://10.0.2.15:8774/v2/cd63ec3d95c14647932aca9248760115/os-volumes?display_name=hello

commit_message:
nova client cinder query param changed to display_name

nova client is not able to show the list of volumes when
querying by name.This is because cinder api accepts only
display_name as query parameter and when qeried with 'name'
parameter returns a empty list

Change-Id: Ie4ffc275d1754052d9e239d8457baf6f7fd53b83
Closes-Bug: #1430415

commit_message:
Remove potential extra work in IpRouteCommand

Variable device_list initialisation and usage is messed up in method
IpRouteCommand.pullup_route. This lead to multiple remove/add same
routes on interface. It's not affect final result, but it do extra work.

By the way, is someone know this method need for? Method's docsting tell
us "Ensures that the route entry for the interface is before all others
on the same subnet." But this is have no sense.

Records in routing table sorted according to destination netmask.  More
specific rules goes first. more common goes last. If someone really need
to change order of records in routing table he should use separate
routing table (See "man ip-route" for info about routing tables and
routing rules. Don't mess routing rules and routing records.)

Change-Id: I35ae4ab9e02a8036d5b823d972c200ce7eaf11c1

Presently, wsgi server allows persist connections. Hence even after the response is sent to the client, it doesn't close the client socket connection. Because of this problem, the green thread is not released back to the pool.

In order to close the client socket connection explicitly after the response is sent and read successfully by the client, you need to configure wsgi_keep_alive = False in neutron.conf."}, {'account_id': 9656, 'date': '2015-01-07 10:51:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

So why is socket_timeout needed here?
It is the reason Nova fix was reverted and Neutron here blocked.

 https://review.openstack.org/#/q/branch:stable/icehouse+topic:bug/1361360,n,z'}, {'account_id': 9303, 'date': '2015-03-10 11:33:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Hi Alan,

This is because while implementing patch for master in neutron/nova I have used socket_timeout and keepalive in same patch where as in cinder/glance I have only used keepalive as 'socket_timeout' solution was applied by other person in separate patch.

Please refer:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/119365/ (socket_timeout patch for cinder)

While backporting these patches to icehouse I have checked that eventlet version 0.15.2 has support to 'socket_timeout' as well as 'keepalive' option."}, {'account_id': 1955, 'date': '2015-03-10 15:59:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

OTOH if keepalive is enough to fix bug 361360, nova/neutron icehouse backports could be amended to drop socket_timeout part.'}, {'account_id': 9303, 'date': '2015-03-10 17:37:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-01-02 06:35:38.000000000', 'message': "Eventlet green threads not released back to pool

Presently, the wsgi server allows persist connections. Hence even after
the response is sent to the client, it doesn't close the client socket
connection. Because of this problem, the green thread is not released
back to the pool.

In order to close the client socket connection explicitly after the
response is sent and read successfully by the client, you simply have to
set keepalive to False when you create a wsgi server.

Added a parameter to take advantage of the new(ish) eventlet socket timeout
behaviour. Allows closing idle client connections after a period of time, eg:

$ time nc localhost 8776
real    1m0.063s

Setting 'client_socket_timeout = 0' means do not timeout.

DocImpact:
Added wsgi_keep_alive option (default=True).
Added client_socket_timeout option (default=900).

SecurityImpact

Closes-Bug: #1361360

commit_message:
Eventlet green threads not released back to pool

Presently, the wsgi server allows persist connections. Hence even after
the response is sent to the client, it doesn't close the client socket
connection. Because of this problem, the green thread is not released
back to the pool.

In order to close the client socket connection explicitly after the
response is sent and read successfully by the client, you simply have to
set keepalive to False when you create a wsgi server.

Icehouse backport note: socket_timeout was dropped, it was introduced
in 0.14[*] and Icehouse eventlet lower bound is 0.13

[*] https://github.com/eventlet/eventlet/commit/7d4916f01462de09cb58853d9de2e85777c2ad5b

DocImpact:
Added wsgi_keep_alive option (default=True).

SecurityImpact

Closes-Bug: #1361360
Change-Id: I3a361d6590d1800b85791f23ac1cdfd79815341b
(cherry picked from commit 8e7a0dbb12082f6159d98a4628fb8a6fcd05e95a)

commit_message:
Verify all quotas before updating the db

Update quota multi-value in one request is not an atomicity operation,
so even if a quota is invalid (Ex: ram less than already used), some values
may change but the return code is 400.

This patch will first check all the quotas before hitting the DB.

Change-Id: I22171c1f1f8171c502f2a9d710cfac38f5b38d85
Closes-Bug: #1291199

commit_message:
storage: add support for value research

This allow the driver to provide a method to search for a certain value.
That is useful to look for period where some metrics are over a certain
value, e.g. finding all metrics (and therefore resources) where the CPU
usage is above 80 %.

Change-Id: I0fab7b80424371b1f4d213ce8aecefe353cce1a6

commit_message:
Adjust Cinder to support FCP on System z systems

There are some platform specific changes needed to allow Cinder to
support FCP on System z: the System z specific format of the device file
paths, adding and removing devices explicitely, and ignoring vHBAs which
are offline.

Partial-Implements blueprint linux-systemz

Change-Id: Ia61c37246235bec618de5bb7f718e8b5520bc9ae

Hi John,

I think some background on how we got to here will help explain things a bit better...

One thing that might be causing some confusion is that there are two issues going on that relate to this and are influencing the implementation. The first one is the reason why we have that "anchor" volume. What we found is that we run into situations where all volumes and the Host objects are deleted in Purity and the iSCSI connections are still active on the initiator.  

So the reason this is a problem is that for our flash array if an initiator is connected and then the host object associated with the initiators IQN is deleted it will disconnect the portal on the targets side. Unfortunately it closes it in a way that causes the iSCSI daemon on the initiator to think it is recoverable and so it will continue to rety to connect to the array and if you run something like "iscsiadm -m session" it shows up in the list. Now, in the case where there is no CHAP in the picture this is kind of OK. Later on if we attach a new volume we create a new host in Purity and the connection goes back to OK the next time the daemon retries. No problem (mostly..).

AFAIK this is actually an error state and is caused by bugs in Cinder/Nova, I spent some time debugging through them to try and get things working.

The following bugs are ones I've filed, but there are a number of others filed that relate to this:

https://bugs.launchpad.net/cinder/+bug/1380742
https://bugs.launchpad.net/cinder/+bug/1388260
https://bugs.launchpad.net/nova/+bug/1385798

Those bugs and associated code changes to go with them are all related to this effort. What we eventually realized though is that for every one of them we fix there always seems to be another one (our release testers appear to have a knack for finding them).

Ok, so now we add CHAP into the picture. We originally were using the provider_auth field (although we had to query/set in initialize_connection instead of the create/ensure_export methods). The idea being that we just use the same credentials for each "host" on the volume objects... not ideal, but probably not so bad considering the larger picture.. Anyway, each time we went to attach a volume we would look for another volume with a host field that matched and if we found it, we use it. If we don't find it we would generate credentials, save them in the database for the current volume, and return the info. 

The issue then is what happens when all the volumes are deleted, the host is deleted, and the iSCSI connection is still "open" but in an error state retrying. This time we try to attach a new volume but we don't know the credentials that were used previously (and are still associated with that broken session) When we create a new host in Purity with freshly generated random credentials we get "locked out" and that iSCSI session that is an error state will never recover... things fall apart pretty soon after since none of the volumes are actually being exposed over iSCSI and it requires someone to manually go in and clear out all the iSCSI/multipath info as it doesn't appear the Nova/Cinder has code to detect these kind of problems and re-initialize/login. 

Here comes *a* solution to the first part of the problem. To prevent us from ever closing the iSCSI portal or deleting the host and getting into an error state we attach an "anchor" volume to the host. This is an unfortunate work-around we've had to do in the past for other misbehaving management systems for the array. The end result is that we become essentially immune to those troublesome disconnect bugs. The flip side being that we will always have a host for each initiator and once we have set CHAP credentials on it we don't know if it is safe to overwrite the secret. This is problematic when we are in a state where the host exists and there are 0 volumes in Cinder. At that point while using the provider_auth field we don't know the CHAP secret, have no way to retreive it, and the initiator will not be able to connect. This is where the "alternative" storage locations start to come into play.

Hopefully that clears up more confusion than it adds... I'm happy to answer any other questions this raises.

TL;DR: We tried the provder_auth field and were unable to get acceptable stability due to bugs with disconnecting iSCSI initiators.'}, {'account_id': 5997, 'date': '2014-12-03 02:50:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

Other backends have this same issue where they can't reliably create and store the CHAP credentials on a volume/host and then retrieve it later at the time of export.   Some drivers make the CHAP credentials cinder.conf entries.   Making a DB table specific for this driver isn't the best route to go either."}, {'account_id': 12924, 'date': '2014-12-04 19:27:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9:

Thanks for the feedback!

Huang: In general it is stored by the management tool (ex: vCenter/ESX), if you are directly connecting without some other tool then yea, the admin would need to create the credentials on the Purity host and then remember them (or save them in the iscsiadm config file or something similar depending on the tool they are using for iSCSI)

While I can completely understand the idea that adding a table for a single driver isn't the best idea, it does sound like it may be useful for others too. If I understand Walter's comment correctly we are not the only ones who suffer from this type of problem, why wouldn't this help those drivers achieve the same goal? (Note: I haven't yet looked to see which drivers actually do this, but I do recall seeing config options for CHAP passwords)

In the initial design we had briefly considered placing credentials in the cinder.conf file to solve this problem, but after floating the idea around there was a lot of pushback due to the perceived security risks. I've also been given feedback from some customers that sharing the same pre-set CHAP credentials for all initiators is not acceptable.

So there are a few options I see for this that have been floated around:

1) local file

Pros: We don't abuse the database or affect other drivers/core code. It works reliably.

Cons: Breaks Active-Active HA, relies on locks, security risks wrt a plain text file storing passwords on the c-vol host.

2) provider_auth field in database:

Pros: We only have to do some light abuse to the database by accessing it in intialize_connection() to query and save volume objects directly. We don't mess with other drivers/core code. It supports the HA scenario.

Cons: It doesn't work reliably and provides a bad user experience.**

** To be fair we could go this route and invest the time to work through all the errors that are associated with this approach... I'm not confident that it is guaranteed to work though. After working through some of them I am pretty hesitant to go this way and it pushes out when we can offer this as a feature quite a long time.

3) New db table

Pros: It supports HA, it works reliably, it doesn't require a plain text file with passwords on the system.

Cons: We add a new table that would be empty and potentially add a maintenance burden for people that are not using our backend.

4) Storing credentials in cinder.conf

Pros: Simple, doesn't affect other drivers, lets us fit in to an existing model.

Cons: Security risks with not generating credentials for each host, customers are not ok with this.

5) Store the same type of data we want to put in the mapping file somewhere else in the database... maybe create a fake volume entry and just keep it around all the time with this as a string in one of its fields.

Pros: Would potentially be as stable as the new table/local file approach. Doesn't add a new table or use a local file.

Cons: Abusing the database so hard

6) ?? I'm still very much open to suggestions... 

Which ones are you guys OK with? I don't want to keep wasting reviewers time with options that are 100% never going to be accepted, but I will need some guidance to make that happen.

Thanks again for all your help thus far."}, {'account_id': 5997, 'date': '2014-12-04 21:45:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

I really feel like this anchor volume thing is a hack and now it's being pushed down to this layer. I don't care if a vendor wants to adopt it, but I have a problem if *I* have to support a bunch of ways to store CHAP auth info and have to consider them all in future CHAP related changes. I want to make it clear that there was no decision on the table approach, but there was a decision on lets see what it looks like. I'm not happy with a new table and an additional chap store to support one vendor's design decision.

Where I would like us to go from here is revisit our current way of storing chap info. I'm not going to be spending time on this right now while we're dealing with an end of a milestone. So I welcome others to help Patrick since he has been very responsive with every hoop we've thrown at him."}, {'account_id': 170, 'date': '2014-12-12 00:55:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 13:

This will also be an excellent topic for the midcycle meetup.'}, {'account_id': 12924, 'date': '2014-12-12 01:28:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 13:

Thanks for your time Mike, I know you are probably swamped with reviews right now.

Just to make sure everyone is on the same page, the anchor volume "hack" in question is specific to our driver and is not something that affects others. It does not cause the problem of there not being a good place to store CHAP credentials for our backend. That problem exists with or without it.'}, {'account_id': 2243, 'date': '2014-12-12 01:51:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 13: Code-Review+2

We had an extensive conversation in this weeks Cinder meeting and it spilled over into channel for about an hour after that.  Fact is it's not the greatest situation, but after everybody finally got the gist of the problem (mostly me, took a long time for me it to click) I think the consensus was that this was a descent approach.  The only other idea that I liked better was backend-metadata, but that's a total rat-hole and filled with all sorts of problems in itself.

Given the consensus and the lack of alternatives I'm ok with it.  It doesn't have a huge tech draw-back that I'm aware of."}, {'account_id': 2243, 'date': '2014-12-12 01:53:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 13:

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-11-25 19:03:06.000000000', 'message': 'Add CHAP support to PureISCSIDriver

This change adds support for iSCSI CHAP with randomly generated
secrets for each initiator. Due to some restrictions with storing meta
data in the backend these secrets need to be stored someplace accessible
from the driver. We have opted for a file on the host running the cinder
service. The file is created with read/write for only the cinder user,
and will contain a mapping between initiators and their configured CHAP
information.

To make this work in a stable fashion and to prevent any “lock-out”s we
are working around some iSCSI issues surrounding disconnecting iSCSI
portals by always keeping a single “anchor” volume attached to a host
which will hold open prevent any connection errors and stop from having
the iSCSI connection from being closed.

Implements: blueprint pure-iscsi-chap-support
Change-Id: I5dfc29602a41ed565af074368947c99aafdc0ab8

commit_message:
Add CHAP support to PureISCSIDriver

This change adds support for iSCSI CHAP with randomly generated
secrets for each initiator. Due to some restrictions with storing meta
data in the backend these secrets need to be stored someplace accessible
from the driver. We will use the driver specific initiator data in the
Cinder DB to store them.

Implements: blueprint pure-iscsi-chap-support
Change-Id: I5dfc29602a41ed565af074368947c99aafdc0ab8

commit_message:
Return 404 when executing net-list-on-dhcp-agent with invalid agent_id

Neutron server returns HTTP code 200 when users execute
net-list-on-dhcp-agent with invalid agent_id.
Users expect HTTP code 404 to be returned.

Change-Id: I41652a9bf4a81835abb6646ea870781472757623
Closes-bug: 1425138

subject: Added Pagerduty to Notification UI
messages:
[{'account_id': 14273, 'date': '2015-03-10 17:49:36.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 12149, 'date': '2015-03-10 18:09:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I'd like to see the PagerDuty specific elements deprecated in favor of a general purpose Webhook or Email choice.  Since PagerDuty is really nothing more than a HTTP webhook/POST request with URL parameters, it really doesn't make sense to start tagging specific API's in the code.  Instead, I prefer a method dependent general purpose implementation whereby the logic to deal with a specific type of notification only implements things like (SMTP, HTTP/HTTPS, SMS) and leaves the details to the end user setting up the notification which would ultimately end up in the data store."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-03-10 18:19:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

commit_message:
Add wwpns to system_metadata for NPIV

NPIV requires that WWPNs be exist on the VM's Fibre Channel adapter.
This change stores the WWPN metadata in the system_metadata (assuming
using the NPIV attach strategy).  This allows for proper
volume_connector rebuilds (which are needed for migrate, destroy,
etc...)

After merge, the destroy path within nova_powervm with NPIV attached
Cinder volumes will work.

Future change sets will add support for aspects such as relocation,
multi I/O Servers, multiple FC ports.

Change-Id: Ie533fa0039ed8b7d7ad8decd21be32ccb23f458e

If the Origin HTTP header passed in the WebSocket handshake does
not match the host, this could indicate an attempt at a

commit_message:
Websocket Proxy should verify Origin header

If the Origin HTTP header passed in the WebSocket handshake does
not match the host, this could indicate an attempt at a
cross-site attack.  This commit adds a check to verify
the origin matches the host.

SecurityImpact

Change-Id: Icda3f8aad0e5dde0be2b12accf03f092634ecde3
Closes-Bug: 1409142

commit_message:
Add operation systems list for TestRail reporter

Add possibility to specify what operation system
releases were used during tests while reporting
results to TestRail.
Also add 'Invalid' bug status to the list of
statuses which are considered as closed and
shouldn't be copied to new results.

Change-Id: I9dd707414044699bd3745b860ac160c43d2e1043
Closes-bug: #1430187

commit_message:
Fixed a problem in recreating masking view in VMAX

When two attach requests happen at the same time on the same volume,
the second one will fail. This patch fixed the problem.

Change-Id: I48450d8bdd4e108cdbc5958951dc5225d6a8592f
Closes-Bug: #1403160

commit_message:
NPIV Volume Connection

This change set provide a simple, single fabric, single FC port
connection for a given Virtual Machine.

This change puts the foundation in (via future change sets) for:
 - Delete connection
 - Multi port
 - Multi I/O Servers

This change does support booting from a NPIV volume.  It does not yet
support delete (though most of the code is in place).  This is due to
the volume connector not generating the same WWPNs.  That needs to be
stored in system metadata, which will be handled in a future change set.

Change-Id: If43f2d6afb56b6c6b6a2265ab0ce18f63d6f9eb4

Release 0.0.2

* Add new section in docs for release_notes

* Write release notes for 0.0.1 and 0.0.2 versions

* Move doc/feature_request/stop_scenario_after_several_errors to implemented

* Various improvements and fixes in docs

commit_message:
Allow importing bundles of packages

Add bundle-import command to allow importing
bundles of packages from local files,
urls or base murano repository.

Change-Id: Ia51fdb242f5730af69dc6825fd48bc7e2e695968
Partially implements: blueprint muranoclient-marketplace-support
