commit_message:
Allow importing packages name

Extend PackageManager.create to allow
importing from external repository by name.
Repository base URL can be set with cli option or env var.

Change-Id: I3107d9319183c11b324753bb96a8082ad7c4e9fb
Partially implements: blueprint muranoclient-marketplace-support

subject: Add minimal diversity requirement for new projects
reviewers: [{'_account_id': 1, 'name': 'James E. Blair', 'email': 'jim@acmegating.com', 'username': 'corvus'}, {'_account_id': 3, 'name': 'Jenkins', 'username': 'jenkins'}, {'_account_id': 7, 'name': 'Jay Pipes', 'email': 'jaypipes@gmail.com', 'username': 'jaypipes'}, {'_account_id': 308, 'name': 'Thierry Carrez', 'email': 'thierry@openstack.org', 'username': 'ttx'}, {'_account_id': 1561, 'name': 'Russell Bryant', 'email': 'rbryant@redhat.com', 'username': 'russellb'}, {'_account_id': 1849, 'name': 'Joe Gordon', 'email': 'joe.gordon0@gmail.com', 'username': 'jogo'}, {'_account_id': 2472, 'name': 'Doug Hellmann', 'email': 'dhellmann@redhat.com', 'username': 'doug-hellmann'}, {'_account_id': 2750, 'name': 'Sean Dague', 'email': 'sean@dague.net', 'username': 'sdague'}, {'_account_id': 2889, 'name': 'Aeva Black', 'email': 'aeva.online@gmail.com', 'username': 'tenbrae'}, {'_account_id': 8443, 'name': 'Georgy Okrokvertskhov', 'email': 'gokrokvertskhov@mirantis.com', 'username': 'gokrokvertskhov'}]
messages:
[{'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2015-03-09 22:26:25.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-03-09 23:23:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-governance-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/85/162785/1/check/gate-governance-docs/8b6ca98//doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 18s'}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2015-03-10 12:05:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

What is your point with this, Joe? Some projects, like Murano, start out as a single-company project, and gradually attract more contribution from other companies over time. Yes, it's great to have diversity in contribution and not have a project be completely dominated by one company. But, joining the openstack/ code namespace is one way to drive more diversity in a project, and by reverting the governance policy to include a diversity requirement again, you're actually going against the spirit of the Big Tent model, which was to open up the openstack/ code namespace to more applicants in order to drive diversity forward. :("}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-03-10 14:09:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

On one side I agree that part of the "OpenStack way" is open collaboration projects gathering multiple parties onto the same set of technology, and prevent company ownership of projects. On the other side, in the past the diversity requirement created a pretty significant chicken-and-egg issue -- that's the reason why it was removed from the incubation requirements. You can't get more contributors or more diversity before you get some form of recognition.

We may encounter a situation in the future where company dominance in a project would prevent open innovation and open development (like core reviewers from company A systematically blocking patches from company B contributors) but maybe we can solve that community problem when/if it happens (by raising the matter to the Technical Committee for resolution).

So I think I'm leaning towards letting people do things and fix issues if they arise, rather than creating rules that hinder progress to protect against an hypothetic problem coming ahead.

I think diversity is an important data point about a project though. Downstream users might want to have that information available so that it factors in their decision to use a project or not. So we could also create a tag describing the diversity level of projects. Like "no single company controlling more than one-third of core/contributors/commits".'}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2015-03-10 14:51:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

I agree with Joe on this. The barrier to entry is quite low now. I don't want to see companies "open-washing" projects and taking advantage of the OpenStack brand. Let's do what we can to encourage collaboration.'}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2015-03-10 16:35:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Jay, see the commit message for the why. Hopefully I fully explained the logic behind this. If not, the commit message needs revising.

Projects have attracted a diverse set of contributors while in stackforge, so I don't think the chicken and egg problem as as bad as it used to be.


  Stackalytics
  Solum
  Rally


http://stackalytics.com/?project_type=stackforge&module=stackalytics&metric=commits&release=all

http://stackalytics.com/?project_type=stackforge&module=solum&metric=commits&release=all

http://stackalytics.com/?project_type=stackforge&module=rally-group&metric=commits&release=all"}, {'account_id': 8443, 'date': '2015-03-10 17:27:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I think that diversity requirements might be harmful for OpenStack community.
If you take a look to projects history you will see two patterns of new projects appearance:
1) Some OpenStack related company adds an initial implementation based on existing solution specific to the company. 
2) Several big companies agrees outside of OpenStack to create a new project and then do this jointly by assigning engineers to them.

Diversity requirement is a barrier for  small companies. Startups are well known innovation generators but they usually create some product before they go to broader community. Now it sounds like startup should have "approval" by other OpenStack players who have resources to allocate for a project. In case of OpenStack there are few companies which have a pool of "free" engineers, so technically they will vote for a project by assigning engineers to them.

I think Thierry proposed the right way to proceed. Be inclusive and make sure that a project follows OpenStack community processes which should allow everyone to contribute to the project. If company who created a project initially is resistive to a new contribution and contributors then this situation should be fixed by TC even by removing this project from OpenStack.'}, {'account_id': 2889, 'date': '2015-03-10 18:00:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

This requirement has served a purpose over the last few years by forcing collaboration between companies that needed external incentives to do so. It also created a chicken-and-egg problem, as Thierry already pointed out, which I think I can break down into a question: in a young project, are the author(s) trying to solve their own immediate problem, or are they building a community that will solve a shared problem together? These are different and complementary goals, but in the absence of community building, a project doesn't feel aligned with OpenStack's mission. Let every single-company-backed project into openstack/* and we step back from one of our core values: community participation.

Every stackforge project whose developers I have recently interacted with all seek a broader participation, but are struggling to get it. (This wasn't always the case, and it may be somewhat self-selected; I'm not claiming all stackforge projects want this.) The perception the authors of said projects have is that, were they to move to openstack/*, they would immediately be validated and gain community participation -- but this perception is, I think, created precisely because we hold this standard today. Lower the standard and we remove the incentive for community building.

Getting participation from other companies takes effort socially as well as technically. I spent a considerable amount of time early in Ironic's development socializing it, finding others in the community that had a similar problem and wanted to collaborate with me on it - then helping those developers dive into the project. I recall the RedDwarfLite  team doing similar work when the project we now know as Trove was formed.

All that said, I am divided on this ... while I value community participation as a core principle of OpenStack, I think our community also values this very highly today (whereas, perhaps, three years ago it needed to be incentivized more strongly). Would a "diversity tag" suffice at encouraging participation // communicating that value to downstream consumers? Perhaps... but I'm not inclined to experiment with that aspect of our community today, so I'm voting with a weak +1 on this.'}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2015-03-10 18:58:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2015-03-10 18:59:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 1, 'date': '2015-03-10 21:07:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I believe the intent of the big-tent is to remove barriers to entry for new projects.  We have seen a number of projects start with a small set of contributors grow.  I think as long as the projects are truly open, it's okay to start small, even with one company, and the healthy projects will be the ones that attract more diverse contributors.  Those can easily be identified -- even with the specific levels that Joe cites -- to help people navigate the sea of projects.  And I think that too is in keeping with the big-tent proposal."}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2015-03-11 16:58:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I'm a huge supporter of the idea that diversity is important for the success of a project.  However, I think the best way to communicate it in the framework we've set up is a tag.  I think we've seen enough successful projects bootstrap usefully with a team from a single company and attract contributors later."}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-03-11 22:20:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

It's also worth noting that projects entering the tent place themselves under the oversight of the Technical Committee, so they already escape their bootstrapping company control at this point.

While I agree the development environment and the rules we live by bring more value to open collaboration projects than to projects that are not diverse (yet), I think a diversity requirement has more drawbacks than benefits. I totally agree that diversity is an interesting data point for project consumers though, so we need to create a tag to objectively describe how diverse a project actually is."}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2015-03-12 02:01:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Jim, Russell you said: "We have seen a number of projects start with a small set of contributors grow" and "I think we've seen enough successful projects bootstrap usefully with a team from a single company and attract contributors later."

Out of curiosity can you name any examples, as some examples would make some interesting data points to look at.


P.S. If I had to vote on this patch myself, I am still not sure how I would vote. But I wanted to have the discussion.'}, {'account_id': 8443, 'date': '2015-03-12 06:11:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I think that Heat project was a bright example of a single company initial effort. 
http://stackalytics.com/?module=heat&release=grizzly&metric=commits

Sahara is another example: http://stackalytics.com/?module=sahara-group&release=grizzly&metric=commits

Both project were able to attract a lot of contributors after incubation. I think in some e-mail thread Heat team mentioned that incubation was important to attract new developers.'}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2015-03-12 11:47:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I really want to unwind this 'though shalt' thinking on everything.

I think that we as a project value diverse projects. I think as a consumer of a project you'd be kind of crazy to put something into production that didn't have a diverse contributor base, because the risk of the project collapsing in the future is high.

However, I think the right thing to do is just say that we value diversity (for the longevity reason) and that consumers should as well (for the same reason). And then point into the pie chart at stackalytics for each project. Honestly, I think those pie charts provide enough detail for people to make up there own mind there, without a TC 'though shalt' on this one."}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2015-03-12 13:58:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Heat and Sahara are great examples, yes.  I can take a stab at defining a tag for this.  It's going to be tough to nail down concrete requirements, but I think we can work out something that provides a broad enough idea about the level of diversity."}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2015-03-12 14:41:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I put up an alternative in the form of a tag: https://review.openstack.org/163851'}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2015-03-12 16:39:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Georgy, good examples thanks. I looked at Manilla as another interesting point and it looks like they easily got diversity while still on stackforge. So it can be done.

That being said, to date it looks like joining the OpenStack namespace more or less means you automatically get new contributors and diversity goes up.

While I am not sure this will stay true in the big tent model as I think part of why people flocked to new projects in the past was the TC was blessing them as the way to go. Under the big tent just because something get added doesn't really mean anything and as the tent grows the dynamics of helping out newly incubated projects may change.  If in a year from now we have several projects in OpenStack that have yet to gain enough diversity to not be overwhelmingly a single company project, then we know this dynamic isn't there anymore. Not sure if that will happen or not, we will find out though."}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2015-03-12 16:40:40.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

While the concern of open washing is a real one, one of the motivations to join OpenStack today is to get the diversity that historically has come along with joining the namespace.'}]

commit_message:
Add minimal diversity requirement for new projects

In the incubation/graduation model contributor diversity was a
requirement for graduation, since one of the goals of incubation was to
increase contributor diversity.

But with the big tent model, where there are significantly more
projects in OpenStack, and we don't pick 'winners' I don't think its
realistic to assume joining OpenStack guarantees a growth in contributor
diversity.

At the same time one of OpenStack's big attractions is community driven
projects where no single company overwhelmingly dominates.

Instead of the previous diversity requirement (Project must have a large and
diverse team of contributors) and a lower bar to at least make sure new
projects aren't overwhelmingly dominated by a single company.

Note: this raises the bar for projects to join OpenStack, but hopefully
in a way that aligns with the big tent initiative.

Change-Id: I98bbfc590677e4e1a89e4dc0d0c81f7fbd183026

commit_message:
Allow importing packages by url

Extend PackageManager.create method to allow
importing from external http/https servers,
maintaining backward compatibility with local file imports

Change-Id: Ibc530f0d0794b8e9fa7dcbc9ff4ead190f5eefd4
Partially implements: blueprint muranoclient-marketplace-support

commit_message:
Network verification status added into CSV

Status of 'verify_networks' action added into clusters CSV report.
DB model ActionLog added.
Column name in CSV report is 'verify_networks_status'.
Installation info filtering by dates fixed. We have datetime in the
InstallationStructure creation_date and modification_date. This causes
wrong filtration by dates results.

Change-Id: Ie758efc6b15d2ab737b16ac724eceb8efaff1aa6
Implements: blueprint export-stats-to-csv
Closes-Bug: #1415520

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-03-10 16:47:24.000000000', 'message': 'Dont look for used_ips on containerless hosts

Ensure there are container_networks on a host before checking for
used_ips. Since hosts with no containers would have no
container_networks these cause the dynamic inventory script to fail.

commit_message:
Set container_networks to a dict rather than None

Ensure container_networks is an empty dict rather than None. This
ensures that if there are no container_networks on a host the
dynamic_inventory won't crash. container_networks is a required host
variable, setting it to an empty dict allows it to be ignored when
looping through if there are no container_networks.

Change-Id: Id0517ac6e06e704cf71964c03f016989db51fde5
Closes-Bug: #1430430

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-06-27 10:05:19.000000000', 'message': 'Split swift-storage element into separate swift service elements

At the moment all swift storage services (acc/cont/obj) are located in the
same element and as a result, any nodes that are used for swift storage
will have all services running on them. However, it would be of benefit to
have the option to split these service accross different nodes. For example,
depending on what type of hardware is being utilised it can often be more
efficient splitting the object services from the account and container services.

This change splits the swift-storage element into four separate elements:

    - swift-storage
    - swift-account
    - swift-container
    - swift-object

Swift storage is now a less loaded element with common storage services and
tools such as rsync and recon. Each other element contains their own separate
packages, configuration files and process start-ups. The three extra elements
also have an element-dependancy on the swift-storage.

Note that I have added the three extra elements in the element-dependancy file
of swift-storage so that the devtest scripts do not break as a result of this
change. If this change is accepted, I will edit devtest_overcloud.py in the
tripleo-incubator environment to include the three extra elements and then
remove the extra elements dependancy introduced here.

Change-Id: I4f1f81f6efb91afa19ead4e3b58d0faea3a015a1

commit_message:
Split swift-storage element into separate swift service elements

At the moment all swift storage services (acc/cont/obj) are located in the
same element and as a result, any nodes that are used for swift storage
will have all services running on them. However, it would be of benefit to
have the option to split these service accross different nodes. For example,
depending on what type of hardware is being utilised it can often be more
efficient splitting the object services from the account and container services.

This change splits the swift-storage element into four separate elements:

    - swift-storage
    - swift-account
    - swift-container
    - swift-object

Swift storage is now a less loaded element with common storage services and
tools such as rsync and recon. Each other element contains their own separate
packages, configuration files and process start-ups. The three extra elements
also have an element-dependancy on the swift-storage.

Note that I have added the three extra elements in the element-dependancy file
of swift-storage so that the devtest scripts do not break as a result of this
change. If this change is accepted, I will edit devtest_overcloud.py in the
tripleo-incubator environment to include the three extra elements and then
remove the extra elements dependancy introduced here.

Change-Id: I4f1f81f6efb91afa19ead4e3b58d0faea3a015a1

commit_message:
order traits returned within events

- we order the traits by key in all the backends except sql. this
keeps sql inline.
- this reverts a patch to sort traits post query in test.

Change-Id: I17009bdb01106dc07659a9198da2090ec63bcf51
Closes-Bug: #1423714

commit_message:
Implements whitelist and blacklist mapping rules

Adds whitelist and blacklist rules to allow passing through a list of
groups from the IdP, after filtering them according to either of these
rules.

Change-Id: If8a26eb184467b64c4076dd1f7d1dcdec1294ec4
Co-Authored-By: Rodrigo Duarte Sousa <rodrigods@lsd.ufcg.edu.br>
Co-Authored-By: Marek Denis <marek.denis@cern.ch>
Partially-Implements: bp mapping-enhancements

commit_message:
Add separate XML and JSON response samples for port binding ext

Removed all port binding extension attributes from the list of
normal neutron port attributes. Updated the port api samples to
remove these attributes as well. Added a new set of samples specifically
for the port binding extended attributes section which do include the
binding-related attributes.

Change-Id: Ibebd1a2420ffeba4928eaae85166f366e05fc931
Closes-bug: #1373420

Volume multi attachments

This spec is a reflection of the work needed to support volume multi attach
capability for Cinder's side of the work.   The Nova spec has already been
approved.

Implements: blueprint multi-attach-volume

commit_message:
Call central's update_status correctly

* Cleaned up the way pool manager calls central's
update_status for create, delete and update.
* Cleaned up pool manager's update_status
* Added some more information to logging statements
when central's update_status and pool manager's
update_status are called
* When a domain is deleted, I see SERVFAIL too being
returned by BIND.  Added that to the list of error codes
to check
* memcache does not seem to store a value of None.
Worked around that bug.
* Updated unit tests
Closes-Bug: 1427433
Closes-Bug: 1427425
Change-Id: Id33381a967afd724ed56ac1d8df648b05a55516c

commit_message:
Return 400 from object server if policy does not exist

Adds a check early in ssync_receiver request handler methods
that verify the policy_index specified in the request headers
actually maps to a policy. If not, return HTTPBadRequest.

* add test for object-server policy validation

Change-Id: I247f5ede67368538dcd7b1c39cd560bfa4b51c64

commit_message:
Add commands to operate snapshot config

Added two commands to dump snapshot config
and provide it for snapshot task

Will download default config and dump it to stdout

fuel snapshot --conf > conf.yaml

Next command will accept config as input and bypass it to snapshot
generation request

fuel snapshot < conf.yaml

This is required to overwrite certain parameters if needed,
some of those are:
- target directory of snapshot generation
- timeout of snapshot generation procedure
- exclusion/inclusion of certain directories

Related-Bug: 1382511
Related-Bug: 1420054

Change-Id: I1ddab26fba1346dad30955289e7d28f4d3aa1562

commit_message:
Expose default snapshot config and allow to pass to snapshot request

Config will be exposed and dumped into file by fuel client.
After this is done, it will be directly consumed by shotgun
or some storage right in nailgun will be implemented to use
user defined config

Original-change: I5e01a7459cefe49a128192d82dd827f02866f909
Cant assign same one, because it was reverted one time

Change-Id: I44f6b426d67bda62d54cbf4a751a78b689e06642
Related-Bug: 1382511
Related-Bug: 1420054

commit_message:
Wrap all lists in JSON object

Affected resources:
    alarm-definition-list   List alarm definitions for this tenant.
    alarm-history         Alarm state transition history.
    alarm-history-list   List alarms state history.
    alarm-list                List alarms for this tenant.
    measurement-list   List measurements for the specified metric.
    metric-list               List metrics for this tenant.
    metric-statistics     List measurement statistics for the specified metric.
    notification-list        List notifications for this tenant.

Change-Id: I9edc42c88c7e16a4fee8310d7dcfcf367bf2bfff

I have no idea what made el7 happy, but as I see `unittest` does not specify six>1.4 as dependency, so if the install ordering randomly changing it can be a random issue.'}, {'account_id': 7118, 'date': '2015-03-11 22:52:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@afezakas : i think it was the upstream change that fixed this

the passing job has the wheel download

 Downloading http://pypi.IAD.openstack.org/packages/2.7/t/testtools/testtools-1.7.1-py2.py3-none-any.whl

while the failing job did

 Downloading http://pypi.IAD.openstack.org/packages/source/t/testtools/testtools-1.7.0.tar.gz (202kB)

So possibly "the tarfile works fine" is not correct in -- also http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-March/058750.html'}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2015-03-12 02:26:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Right, as discussed on list:
 - installs from source run more code and run into a pip limitation when an imported thing needs to be upgraded.
 - there is also a bug in unittest2 - it needs a versioned six dependency

commit_message:
Don't use packaged unittest2

Let pip install unittest2; pip installation can conflict with the
packaged version.

Change-Id: Iec9b35174ac68ebf713cd7462d7b5a82583d6e22
Partial-Bug: #1430592

commit_message:
Set os_region_name for cinder

Region name should be set to nova.conf and cinder.conf so that
cinder volume can work in multiregion env.

Closes-Bug: #1429738
Change-Id: Ib20911c24d8daabc07e6515f4a23a745d77593ff

commit_message:
Remove the kesytone admin token from swift

The keystone admin token supposed to be used only
for setting up keystone and it should not be used
in any other service config.

Change-Id: Iaa9be1878e89a6bc3a84a0c57fc6f5cecc371d2f

commit_message:
Add package mongodb to files/rpms/zaqar-server

The command mongo, used in lib/zaqar, is part of the package mongodb.
At the moment only mongodb-server is listed in files/rpms/zaqar-server,
mongodb has to be added there.

Change-Id: I60edeae6760addad62b9b61c3dcdecc2ff01cba7
Closes-bug: #1430939

Shares should be able to be visible for all tenants - additional attr
'is_public=True/False' will work for it.

this new column (default is public=False).

'get_all'.

to add public shares from all projects when 'public=True' is provided.

commit_message:
Add public attr for shares

For the moment only owner of share can see it. There are use cases when
we may want to share it for all, for example, only with "ro" access.

Shares should be able to be visible for all tenants - additional attr
'is_public=True/False' will work for it.

Add 'is_public' column to share model and add migration which creates
this new column (default is public=False).

Allow to pass new 'public' param to share api methods 'create' and
'get_all'.

Change DB API functions 'share_get_all_by_project' and '_share_get_all_with_filters'
to add public shares from all projects when 'public=True' is provided.

Implements bp level-of-visibility-for-shares

Change-Id: I444f5b3aceea8322d947722e945ff81c0b2b84cc

commit_message:
Add check_ready between each container start

Prevents race condition where keystone starts
before postgres is ready.

Change-Id: I38a3d43d6a3f023fbc45e64e85a75619c1bd91ab
Closes-Bug: #1430348

commit_message:
Added checks for mandatory parameters in a plan file

Checking that following keys are present in the plan file:
- artifacts
- artifact name
- artifact content
- artifact language_pack

Change-Id: I45c6ef72a878ee0259cf284f60eee8c502152119
Closes-Bug: #1429973

commit_message:
Set rootfstype=ramfs for low memory Ironic nodes

When running with low memory (<1024), we need to switch from the default
rootfstype from tmpfs to ramfs to ensure nodes can decompress deployment
ramdisks.

Backport of commit 756c842a7743a84a084b4cc211998e3fdd171592.

commit_message:
Remove my_ip from cinder.conf

The current issue is that if we deploy c-vol service on a separate
machine, my_ip and SERVICE_HOST will be different, because my_ip is
the machine where c-vol service is running and SERVICE_HOST points
to the machine where the cinder api service is running. If my_ip of
c-vol in cinder.conf is set to the IP of c-api, it will cause the
issue that the volume is unable to attach. The issue can be resolved
by removing my_ip from cinder.conf.

Change-Id: I699c0b5297c60e9f9934f74684abf563f4b0e977
closes-bug: #1428013

commit_message:
Add data-processing service for Sahara

When registering endpoint with data_processing Keystone transforms it
into data-processing. This problem causes sahara to not find the
endpoint afterwards

We need to have two endpoint for correct working tempest and horizon
with devstack. After resolving bug in tempest and horizon need to remove
old data_processing endpoint

Change-Id: I97827d23ffe8a1218abd61e76804b918b1b7cbe0
Partial-bug: #1356053
(cherry picked from commit 77f82f38496f364b7cc6d2a5bc8b45432934a130)

commit_message:
Remove page_size from compute GET servers

The compute v2 GET API "List servers" doc reference a 'page_size'
pagination param that is never used in the nova GET servers code;
only limit and marker are supported.

Change-Id: I9b434fd46e38a9e5a273dd4ccb38f2a22a1d071d
Closes-Bug: 1428280

commit_message:
Switch fuel-agent to single `parted` call

Firing multiple `parted` calls within short period of time produces
'device or resource is busy' error. Switching to single call should
significally reduce the probability of that error appearing.

Change-Id: I95608ef6718e2b6ce4513f030730eb85aba85f16

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-02-13 16:39:42.000000000', 'message': 'IBP: Added sleep 10 after node reboot

The reason for this fix to appear is that Cobbler runs reboot
command and reports reboot succeeded, but astute manages to get the type
of node OS via Mcollective (/etc/nailgun_systemtype) and runs node erasing
procedure for the nodes which type!=target. Erasing procedure in turn
kicks sysrq trigger which breaks the node.

Change-Id: I98cc29256fb9a807aba9b6dddc500864c74bd735
Closes-Bug: 1420256
'}]
commit_message:
IBP: Added sleep 10 after node reboot

The reason for this fix to appear is that Cobbler runs reboot
command and reports reboot succeeded, but astute manages to get the type
of node OS via Mcollective (/etc/nailgun_systemtype) and runs node erasing
procedure for the nodes which type!=target. Erasing procedure in turn
kicks sysrq trigger which breaks the node.

Change-Id: I98cc29256fb9a807aba9b6dddc500864c74bd735
Closes-Bug: 1420256

commit_message:
Update the Infrastructure project homepage URL

The wiki article at the old Infrastructure project homepage URL
contained only information which is now redundant with what is in
the reference/projects.yaml file and governance.openstack.org site
content, along with a link to what is now the new URL.

Change-Id: Ie23b5367749024578b7948348d13aae1995c38ac

commit_message:
Revert "Trim ansible's output to console.log"

This reverts commit a9244537d62662ab3342d1c1bdb74e3b1f23ad0e.

Revert is required because this patch removes all output from the
console log, rather than reducing the verbosity as intended.

Change-Id: I33700ca75ea16e6eb93f2e43d814d70960145ff4

commit_message:
Fix the final PEP8 errors

Fix PEP8 E126,E127,E128 errors, which were the only ones remaining.

Fix PEP8 errors:
E126: continuation line over-indented for hanging indent
E127: continuation line over-indented for visual indent
E128: continuation line under-indented for visual indent

Remove the ignore= entries for flake8 in tox.ini

Change-Id: I919551121d85d2aab528f4fa5ecdb3cfd940557a

commit_message:
Add AMT-PXE-Driver Power&Management&Vendor Interface

Introduce a new driver pxe-amt to extend Ironic's range to desktops.
AMT (Active Management Technology)/vPro is widely used in desktops
to remotely control the power, similar to IPMI in servers.
It will use AMT as power management and PXE as deploy management.
This patch only provides basic operations to support the workflow of
remotely deploying on AMT/vPro system.

This adds power, management and it's own vendor interface.
This also adds a new fake-amt driver.

Implements blueprint amt-pxe-driver

[{'created': '2015-03-11 21:48:16.000000000', 'message': "Fix kwargs['instance'] KeyError in @reverts_task_state decorator

We use @reverts_task_state everywhere in the compute manager and we
ensure that 'instance' is a parameter to the decorator method via
@utils.expects_func_args('instance'), however, that only ensures there
is an instance argument, not that it's in args or kwargs (either is fine
for what expects_func_args checks).

The reverts_task_state decorator can get a KeyError when checking
kwargs['instance'] and fail to revert the task_state on the instance,
which can leave us in a bad state where non-admins can't delete the
instance if the task_state is not None (and the reset-state API is
admin-only).

This fixes the KeyError in the decorator by normalizing the args/kwargs
list into a single dict that we can pull the instance from.

Also adds a warning log if we fail the instance update since it
shouldn't happen and we want to know if it does because of the
aforementioned problems with deleting orphaned instances.

There isn't a specific unit test added for this since moving
kwargs['instance'] above the try/except in reverts_task_state makes a
lot of tests fail already if you don't have the normalize code.

Closes-Bug: #1423952

Change-Id: I70f464120c798422f9a3d601b7cdf3b0a8320690
(cherry picked from commit c43f2b0d708f0f4b37850d2917c0abcc13b8789b)
"}]
commit_message:
Fix kwargs['instance'] KeyError in @reverts_task_state decorator

We use @reverts_task_state everywhere in the compute manager and we
ensure that 'instance' is a parameter to the decorator method via
@utils.expects_func_args('instance'), however, that only ensures there
is an instance argument, not that it's in args or kwargs (either is fine
for what expects_func_args checks).

The reverts_task_state decorator can get a KeyError when checking
kwargs['instance'] and fail to revert the task_state on the instance,
which can leave us in a bad state where non-admins can't delete the
instance if the task_state is not None (and the reset-state API is
admin-only).

This fixes the KeyError in the decorator by normalizing the args/kwargs
list into a single dict that we can pull the instance from.

Also adds a warning log if we fail the instance update since it
shouldn't happen and we want to know if it does because of the
aforementioned problems with deleting orphaned instances.

There isn't a specific unit test added for this since moving
kwargs['instance'] above the try/except in reverts_task_state makes a
lot of tests fail already if you don't have the normalize code.

Closes-Bug: #1423952

Change-Id: I70f464120c798422f9a3d601b7cdf3b0a8320690
(cherry picked from commit c43f2b0d708f0f4b37850d2917c0abcc13b8789b)

commit_message:
Enable Neutron in neutronclient functional test job

nova-network is used in python-neutronclient functional test job now.
No endpoint is configured for Nuetron, and neutronclient funcational
test will fail completely.

Change-Id: I00e56cab162941bb9d9bd84d0fffd66e9698bb4c
Related-Bug: #1429289

commit_message:
Wait for keystone to be fully initialized

Previously we used check_for_keystone() which just checked that the
keystone v2.0 public endpoint was responding to a http GET. Instead we
now check that making an admin-level request via the keystone client
works correctly. This ensures that the admin tenant and admin role all
exist before proceeding with the rest of the script. Doing so
guarantees that we don't run into a race condition that can occur if
you are starting up multiple containers simultaneously. The problem
can arise if you make two concurrent calls to crux user-create that
both potentially try to create the admin role and tenant. For example
the call in this script and another in keystone/start.sh. See Bug
1429104 for more details.

We could immediately bail out of this script if the new keystone check
fails and stop the container from starting. However I preferred not to
do this and use the wait_for script because it seemed a little more
elegant and also I thought it could result in a faster start up time
e.g. waiting 1sec to check keystone again maybe faster than tearing
down the container and starting it back up again and may generate
less churn in the container logs.

wait_for is a script I gratuitously stole from
openstack/tripleo-incubator/tree/master/scripts. The tripleo team don't
believe in doing releases from that repo, so other than a git checkout
of master there really isn't a nice cross distro way to consume it. If
we think the script could be useful elsewhere then maybe it could
eventually be moved into ./base container

Change-Id: Ic27a9c5d050f0cb9103acf5d5e28840a313c3239
Closes-Bug: 1429104

commit_message:
Allow capabilities for scheduling from Nova

This spec talks about how capabilities may be
used from Nova for scheduling and how an operator
can configure nodes with capabilities.

NOTE: This spec is more of an agreement on how to
use capabilities for scheduling after the recent
patch merged in Nova (https://review.openstack.org/#/c/141012/).
This spec doesn't propose anything new.  The
actual work for a generic way for mentioning hardware
capabilities/driver capabilities has been bumped to L
and will be looked on in the next release.

Change-Id: I256d286e93fa2256b94af6d884f884cba4a51379

This is not the right way to solve this at all.

There is already an implementation for how to auto-determine the path:

SCRIPTNAME=$(basename $0)
SCRIPT_HOME=$(dirname $(readlink -f $0))
if [ -d $SCRIPT_HOME/../share/diskimage-builder ]; then
    export _PREFIX=$SCRIPT_HOME/../share/diskimage-builder
else
    export _PREFIX=$SCRIPT_HOME/..
fi
export _LIB=$_PREFIX/lib

ELEMENTS_PATH is then set to $_PREFIX/elements if it is unset in the environment.

It is only complicated by the fact that element-info is python. What you can do is write a bin script that does the logic above after $SCRIPT_HOME execute it from both places. so

export _PREFIX=$($SCRIPT_HOME/dib-get-prefix))

And then do the same thing in element-info. Bonus points if dib-get-prefix is written in python and has tests, but a shell script is fine too.'}, {'account_id': 11599, 'date': '2015-03-12 14:21:08.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Fixes element-info -d ubuntu errors

This patch adds the default elements path in the $ELEMENTS_PATH
environment variable. It also appends the default $ELEMENTS_PATH
if user had exported the $ELEMENTS_PATH in the enviroment.

Change-Id: Ic9da7c2d87aa13c6cf110a94ca521c8f6a1b0208
Closes-bug: #1265650

I think this makes the window smaller, but it is still there - the scheduler should not fail create requests until it has received updates from all of the volume services. That takes time, even if it only takes a few seconds with this patch.

I think this approach can be used together with the sleep-for-thirty-seconds-if-we-haven't-been-up-that-long-then-reschedule approach - this patch means that we're far less likely to trigger the other one, which is good."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-02-24 12:32:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1

Hey Winston, just curious... aren't we supposed to be reporting updates at init from the driver anyway?  In which case I suppose the problem here is specific to restarting the scheduler service?  But that seems ok because the scheduler service issues the update call.  So I guess I'm not following exactly what "startup" issue this is looking at.  Maybe you can help me understand what I'm missing?'}, {'account_id': 2759, 'date': '2015-02-25 03:10:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

Hi John, yes, this change is all about restoring the original behavior scheduler had when restarting scheduler service.  And yes, scheduler does issues the update call in init_host() to all vol services, but that call should be issued *AFTER* the RPC initialization is done so that it is able to receive the stats from vol services.  But Wanghao's commit moved init_host() ahead of RPC init in Manager base class because for vol service need vol manager to get ready before RPC."}, {'account_id': 12493, 'date': '2015-02-25 12:41:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-02-24 10:23:55.000000000', 'message': "Allow scheduler to receive volume stats when starting service

Filter scheduler relies on volume services to report their stats in
order to make decisions - this nature makes scheduler service a bit
special when it starts because it can't really do anything without
knowning stats of avilable volume backend.  So the original
implementation of Filter Scheduler added a hook in init_host() to
ask all volume services to send their stats immediately (volume RPC
call 'publish_service_capabitlies()'), this reduced the chance of a
new volume being set to 'error' state becuase scheduler has no
knowledge of backends to minimum.

             Scheduler       RPC Exchanges    Volume Service(s)
service start | RPC init                          |
              | init_host()                       |
              | --pub_src_caps()-->|  ----------> | (vol fanout)
              |     <-------------  |<-vol stats--| (sch fanout)

However, commit 65fa80c361f71158cc492dfc520dc4a63ccfa419 moved
init_host() ahead of service RPC initialization because for volume
services, service initialization should be done before the service
starts accepting RPC requests.  This change unfortunately invalided
scheduler service's init_host() because that needs to be done *AFTER*
RPC is ready (a queue is bound to scheduler fanout exchange).  The
result is scheduler asks vol service to send update, but it misses
the information it asked for because the its queue hasn't been
created and bound to the fanout queue yet.  So scheduler always has
to wait for the next update from volume services to be able to work
properly.

             Scheduler       RPC Exchanges    Volume Service(s)
service start | init_host()                       |
              | --pub_src_caps()-->|  ----------> | (vol fanout)
              |   (vol stats lost)  |<-vol stats--| (sch fanout)
              | RPC init                          |

This change add a new hook to Manager class called init_hook_with_rpc()
to allow services like scheduler to do something once RPC is ready.
This should restore scheduler's behavior before commit
65fa80c361f71158cc492dfc520dc4a63ccfa419.

Change-Id: If6cf9030eb44c39a06ec501ac5c049d460782481
Closes-bug: #1409012

commit_message:
Allow scheduler to receive volume stats when starting service

Filter scheduler relies on volume services to report their stats in
order to make decisions - this nature makes scheduler service a bit
special when it starts because it can't really do anything without
knowning stats of avilable volume backend.  So the original
implementation of Filter Scheduler added a hook in init_host() to
ask all volume services to send their stats immediately (volume RPC
call 'publish_service_capabitlies()'), this reduced the chance of a
new volume being set to 'error' state because scheduler has no
knowledge of backends to minimum.

             Scheduler       RPC Exchanges    Volume Service(s)
service start | RPC init                          |
              | init_host()                       |
              | --pub_src_caps()-->|  ----------> | (vol fanout)
              |     <-------------  |<-vol stats--| (sch fanout)

However, commit 65fa80c361f71158cc492dfc520dc4a63ccfa419 moved
init_host() ahead of service RPC initialization because for volume
services, service initialization should be done before the service
starts accepting RPC requests.  This change unfortunately invalidated
scheduler service's init_host() because that needs to be done *AFTER*
RPC is ready (a queue is bound to scheduler fanout exchange).  The
result is scheduler asks vol service to send update, but it misses
the information it asked for because its queue hasn't been created
and bound to the fanout queue yet.  So scheduler always has to wait
for the next update from volume services to be able to work properly.

             Scheduler       RPC Exchanges    Volume Service(s)
service start | init_host()                       |
              | --pub_src_caps()-->|  ----------> | (vol fanout)
              |   (vol stats lost)  |<-vol stats--| (sch fanout)
              | RPC init                          |

This change adds a new hook to Manager class called init_hook_with_rpc()
to allow services like scheduler to do something once RPC is ready.
This should restore scheduler's behavior before commit
65fa80c361f71158cc492dfc520dc4a63ccfa419.

Change-Id: If6cf9030eb44c39a06ec501ac5c049d460782481
Partial-bug: #1409012

adopt namespace-less oslo imports

oslo.config is now deprecated, so switching from oslo.config to right
package oslo_config. similarly oslo.serialization also deprecated, it
is also switched to oslo_serialization from oslo.serialization.

Closes-bug: #1416516

commit_message:
Interface must go prior to its subinterfaces

Each interface should go prior to its subinterfaces in transformations section of network scheme.
So, appropriate ports ordering was added.
Also, add_port() function was fixed.

Closes-Bug: #1430738
Change-Id: I0c8d23b20e5e701cac0f620062fa09e3ff4c3186

commit_message:
Adjust method for trimming ansible output debug information

This patch adjusts the method introduced in
I98fb57a56c1b7ddd6558e265cf6e65b159a05123 to trim the debug information
from the ansible output.

This adjustment allows the output to come to the console immediately,
instead of piping to a file and doing the processing after the ansible
run is complete.

Change-Id: I515adcad34ef76b8ea47fe90bc6572fb3aec1d2c
Partial-bug: #1425482

commit_message:
Removed ubuntu target images from ISO

We are not allowed to re-distribute
ubuntu packages as well as ubuntu images.
We are going to build ubuntu target images
just before we start actual provision process.

This patch removes ubuntu target images from ISO.

Change-Id: Ic1b320bd4becd9deef0aaf326f8f05957958ca1c
Implements: blueprint consume-external-ubuntu

@Joel

thanks for the comments.

re: usage
yes there will be further patches that will use this code.

re: key manager class
i wanted to start this off a thin wrapper around the key manager as our needs are light at the moment. further work will need to be done to migrate towards a proper key manager class.

my hope is that once Castellan has landed we will revisit this code and refactor the implementation use a more thorough key manager class. currently it didn't make sense given the way we want to use the manager. we have some simple cases of passwords in our database that need to be removed. my thinking is that we can, for the time, replace those passwords with the references provided from the external manager.

i agree with your inline comments, and i think that's the direction we are ultimately moving towards. this is just our first step."}]

commit_message:
Adding barbican client and keymgr module

This change implements the key manager abstraction module and barbican
client helper for the improved secret storage spec.

Changes
* adding barbican module
* adding keymgr module
* adding a session method to the keystone module
* adding tests for keymgr module
* adding documentation for keymgr usage

SecurityImpact

Implements: blueprint improved-secret-storage
Change-Id: I462f2f6cdc35470f75771b5beca10899a591b46a

commit_message:
Add config option to override url for versions

The versions url returns the wrong data when cinder api is behind
a proxy. This adds a new config option so it can be set properly.

DocImpact

Change-Id: I46a90120b21e43bf8dca9e5f0efdf339f0d3e8e6
Closes-Bug: #1384379

commit_message:
Add entry point definitions

Add entry point definitions for the ovn ml2 mechanism driver and the
l3 service plugin.  This makes configuration to use these drivers
easier.

Change-Id: Ibcfcab49514177acd8200bc726642d6b1f5fa0e1

commit_message:
Define the behavior for a 405 response

This commit adds language to the API reference describing the behavior
of the service when a request is sent to a recognized API URI, but the
request does not use a supported HTTP method.

Change-Id: I31143ea0f7e6727b7f80f83dced10c68c44ffe1a

commit_message:
rest: uses search query to filter on metric aggregation

This patches change the metric aggregation for resources so it uses a
dedicated endpoint that accepts the same kind of filtering than the
search queries. That allows for much powerful filtering on resources.

Change-Id: I05ab0b7dd5548ae39d061c46768618ea1455d1e0

rest: change metric aggregation URL

This changes the metric aggregation URL as we are going to add an
endpoint to do aggregation over metric via resources in a subsequent
patch.

commit_message:
Fix Incorrect parameters for Neutron Port APIs

1. Query parameters
   Add Query parameters for List API.
2. Read-only parameters for Binding Extension
   Remove vif_detail and vif_type from Request parameter for Add/Update APIs.
3. Details for xsd:dict parameter
   Add sub parameters of xsd:dict parameters such as allowed_address_pairs and extra_dhcp_opts.
4. device_id and device_owner
   Add device_id and device_owner for Create/Update APIs

Change-Id: I8baffc669d1e16260ae156d2718029cfb3513fb8
Closes-Bug: #1425783

commit_message:
Standardize REST API pagination params

The limit/marker API documentation is very inconsistent across projects and
this patch set standardizes it by:

* Creating a common_project.ent file that contains entities to be shared
  across multiple projects
* Adding the limit/marker param entities to the common file
* Updating the existing references to limit/marker to use the common file

This patch set also adds the missing limit/marker params to the appropriate
cinder docs.

Change-Id: Ic95d2d88cb5caa804fb45fc62b61665a97e4dde9

commit_message:
Don't install nova's rootwrap file in light mode

Since we don't install Nova in light mode, /etc/nova/rootwrap.d/
doesn't exist, thus stack.sh would fail.

Change-Id: Iabb41422d8daae5a52d03957d099d187f7e1a0ad

searched, in this order: `PREFIX/include' (normally `/usr/local/include'

My opinion is completely opposite. Using complicated things where they are not necessary is equal to being arrogant. I did not know about this non-obvious make capability of building make non-existent make files in run time. I'm ashamed with that but I think, many people are not familiar with this feature. Explicit is better than implicit. Moreover, many people don't like tools which are smarter than they are and prefer to follow KISS principle. That is a good point to teach people about make via complicated code, but that is not our goal. Our goal is to make high quality community product. That means we need to keep things as simple as possible to be able to maintain our product and make people able to contribute to it.

I don't see copy-paste pieces in this patch. I see some problems in the current code. I'am trying to solve those problems."}, {'account_id': 13194, 'date': '2014-11-29 10:14:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

> Moreover, many people don't like tools which are smarter than they are and prefer to follow KISS principle.

This is not a KISS because you are already changing something. So principle here is "Don't Make It Dumber".

Also, people who don't like 'tools that are smarter then them' usually learn over the tools, rising their own awareness of tool and therefore rendering tools dumber then they are. Otherwise this principle would be used by the lazy people to destroy everything they see and don't like (and this is happened indeed a few times).

However, I see this change as a political and deny to participate in this review anymore.'}, {'account_id': 13194, 'date': '2014-12-01 08:05:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

> Using complicated things where they are not necessary is equal to being arrogant.

Including dynamically built files into a makefile a is well documented and a widely used technique. A well known use case is generating the dependencies of a C source file (see http://scottmcpeak.com/autodepend/autodepend.html)

> I did not know about this non-obvious make capability of building make non-existent make files in run time.

It's better to read the documentation (google for "makefile automatic dependencies GCC") instead of "fixing" the perfectly working code.

> Our goal is to make high quality community product.

There are quite a number of known issues/broken code, let's fix instead of re-inventing the wheel (https://bugs.launchpad.net/fuel/+bug/1397845)

> I don't see copy-paste pieces in this patch

Have a look at packages/deb/debian-boot/initrd.mk.
By the way, spreading the code which handles netboot preparation over several files (which is what the patch being reviewed actually does) does not make the code more clear, modular, or otherwise better in any way.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-12-31 11:27:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified-1

commit_message:
Refactoring installer kernel version defining

* Substituted including non-existents make file
  (which make builds in run time) with more obvious construction.
  Hope it makes this place more clear for those who is not an expert in
  GNU make. It is just for the sake of Fuel openness.

Change-Id: I50e8efdb44cdabd516a958de93b95b05f7e5687c
Closes-Bug: 1397259

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-02-11 15:08:32.000000000', 'message': 'IBP: Added sleep 10 after node reboot

The reason for this fix to appear is that Cobbler runs reboot
command and reports reboot succeeded, but astute manages to get the type
of node OS via Mcollective (/etc/nailgun_systemtype) and runs node erasing
procedure for the nodes which type!=target. Erasing procedure in turn
kicks sysrq trigger which breaks the node.

Change-Id: I98cc29256fb9a807aba9b6dddc500864c74bd735
Closes-Bug: 1420256
'}]
commit_message:
IBP: Added sleep 10 after node reboot

The reason for this fix to appear is that Cobbler runs reboot
command and reports reboot succeeded, but astute manages to get the type
of node OS via Mcollective (/etc/nailgun_systemtype) and runs node erasing
procedure for the nodes which type!=target. Erasing procedure in turn
kicks sysrq trigger which breaks the node.

Change-Id: I98cc29256fb9a807aba9b6dddc500864c74bd735
Closes-Bug: 1420256

commit_message:
Add Digest intrinsic function

Digest intrinsic function takes an algorithm name (e.g. md5, sha512,
etc) and a string value and will resolve to the corresponding hash of
the value.

Usage:

    pwd_hash: { digest: ['sha512', { get_param: raw_password }] }

Implements: blueprint digest-intrinsic-function
Change-Id: I7b5332462013cf8063fadec1654fa9f364da45de

commit_message:
Ubuntu repos improvements

* description added to the Repositories setting
* all repo names are replaced by editable name fields
* added editable priority field to each repo
* headers added to the repo table

Change-Id: Ia4b661851446368b7b264044150ad8fd9d090d3b

  properly get the regex version.

commit_message:
qpid: Always auto-delete queue of DirectConsumer

In case of the call()er die, the queue used to reply must be
automatically deleted, otherwise they will never been deleted.

This is done in the same way as the rabbit drivers does,
by enabling auto-delete on this queue.

Change-Id: Ib01981d704b8849e0115791ff90fbb74cbac421f
Closes-Bug: #1374519

commit_message:
Infer router instead of requiring it

* This change allows using our LB functionality through Horizon.
* It still requires that a router ID be given, however instead of
  requiring it from the user, it can be inferred from the subnet id by
  going through the neutron database.
* The limitations are:
  1) The subnet used by the Pool must be associated with a router.
  2) If an external subnet is used for the VIP, then the router
  associated with the pool's subnet must have its gateway set.

Fixes: MNP-25

This commit is backported from previous project
`python-neutron-plugin-midonet`:
https://github.com/midonet/python-neutron-plugin-midonet/commit/\
94e8378e423e4355ce35b782c15393889a909c87

Change-Id: I80837416b9944b2adb2e6b1b500f73d065a906c5

commit_message:
1) When detecting flow sync issue, when a flow is reached to the
controller with no metadata start the bootstrap flow installation.
2) Create a bootstrap flow installation method
Closes-Bug: #1429600

Change-Id: Ia48729dcb892a071b5b0927bac758151f724ca72

commit_message:
Adjust health check for Cobbler container

Ubuntu profile in Cobbler will not be available during master node
bootstrap because of missing netboot files.

Change-Id: I4982ecd59d034a5112f07605eb2ea23c4beee3bc
Implements: separate-mos-from-linux

commit_message:
Create ansible log file and directory

This commit adds the ansible log file to the aio bootstrap script
and creates a vanilla logging directory that will allow us to collect
additional information on what is happening within a given ansible run.

Partial-Bug: #1425482
Partial-Bug: #1428744

We are not allowed to re-distribute ubuntu debian-installer
kernel and initrd. So, we are going to download these files
from one of user defined ubuntu repos. We implemented this
as a pre-provision task which is supposed to run a shell
script.

This patch removes original ubuntu debian-installer
ramdisk and kernel and substitutes them with zero files just

Implements: blueprint consume-external-ubuntu
'}]
commit_message:
Removed debian-installer initrd and kernel

We are not allowed to re-distribute ubuntu debian-installer
kernel and initrd. So, we are going to download these files
from one of user defined ubuntu repos. We implemented this
as a pre-provision task which is supposed to run a shell
script.

This patch removes original ubuntu debian-installer
ramdisk and kernel and substitutes them with zero files just
to make sure cobbler is able to create corresponding Distro.

Change-Id: Ie154cfdf3c6e9b4f063ab859cd050be6faa1707e
Implements: blueprint consume-external-ubuntu

commit_message:
Allow full v3 authentication

Allow authenticating with ids and fetching domain scoped tokens. Changes the
acceptable parameters to more specific parameter names so that _id and _name
parameters can no longer be confused.

This tries to not change the config file and existing credential loading paths.

Closes-Bug: #1420605
Change-Id: If5a889be5826d60bf61dbb84661a5896cb094875

commit_message:
Func test conf to specify boot config

This adds a functional test config option boot_config_env which
can specify a path to an environment file which defines boot config
resources for any test which needs the heat agent projects.

By default this value points to boot_config_none_env.yaml, which assumes
the image is already completely configured with the heat agent projects.

The aim is that in the gate jobs the following will be set:
boot_config_env=/opt/stack/new/heat-templates/hot/software-config/boot-config/test_image_env.yaml

And the image_ref will refer to the latest built image in
http://tarballs.openstack.org/heat-test-image/

Change-Id: I1fa09bf3a8be248829061b931dd773973732fa52

commit_message:
Add lockutils.get_lock_path() function

Provide an API to discover the path being used to store external lock
files. Tempest will use this to set up some additional locking and to
test its own behavior. Other projects might use it for error reporting
or other purposes.

Change-Id: Iad40c67072333cc25a6d3e39d7535ff14b573504

[{'created': '2015-03-12 01:58:02.000000000', 'message': "Use AWS::EC2::EIP for test_server_cfn_init

Many (most) clouds won't have the assumed network to directly ping/ssh
to the default IP address. This changes test_server_cfn_init to assign
a floating IP, and use that to ping and ssh to the server.

It also moves the ping to the end of the test. This was initially

Change-Id: Ia9404289b2f9632883a479ccb435cbf6c51fcf2f
"}]
commit_message:
Use AWS::EC2::EIP for test_server_cfn_init

Many (most) clouds won't have the assumed network to directly ping/ssh
to the default IP address. This changes test_server_cfn_init to assign
a floating IP, and use that to ping and ssh to the server.

It also moves the ping to the end of the test. This was initially
meant to catch regressions in a co-gated neutron, but it is no longer
required for a heat-only test.

Change-Id: Ia9404289b2f9632883a479ccb435cbf6c51fcf2f

We're already configuring Neutron in Overcloud, but Nova used its

and not Neutron.

Change-Id: Id2d5a5a0aa1ca087de714880ef1ea98484b06849
"}, {'created': '2015-03-11 20:57:30.000000000', 'message': "Puppet: Configure neutron_api_class on controller

We're already configuring Neutron in Overcloud, but the controller
is still configured to use the default Nova neutron_api_class for
default configuration for networking, which means it used Nova Network
and not Neutron. This causes some of the Nova API is_neutron
checks to behave incorrectly.

This patch updates the controller to use nova::network::neutron (like
we already do on the overcloud_compute.pp role). As part of the change
several of the compute specific hiera settings for the
nova::network::neutron class have been moved to common.yaml.

Change-Id: Id2d5a5a0aa1ca087de714880ef1ea98484b06849
"}]
commit_message:
Puppet: Configure neutron_api_class on controller

We're already configuring Neutron in Overcloud, but the controller
is still configured to use the default Nova neutron_api_class for
default configuration for networking, which means it used Nova Network
and not Neutron. This causes some of the Nova API is_neutron
checks to behave incorrectly.

This patch updates the controller to use nova::network::neutron (like
we already do on the overcloud_compute.pp role). As part of the change
several of the compute specific hiera settings for the
nova::network::neutron class have been moved to common.yaml.

Change-Id: Id2d5a5a0aa1ca087de714880ef1ea98484b06849

Since this change was split from the original change to have more discussion regarding the volume type name change. Copied the responses from the original changes:

A couple of reasons that we should allow changing volume type name:
1.Please think about the use case: the administrator is preparing the volume types. He has created a bunch of volume types and added extra specs and qos specs and entered descriptions. Later he notices he has typed something wrong in the names…crap…now he has to delete those volume types and start over, what a pain!

2.Volumes table or other table references volume type by volume type id, changing volume type name should not cause any reference issues.

3.Even a volume created with volume type A, changing volume type A to be called volume type B should have minimum impact on the volume. I notice that cinder allows updating extra specs on the volume type when it is in use. Updating extra specs of volume type has more impact on volumes than changing volume type name.

4.Changing volume type name is only for administrators so it is not expected to happen frequently.'}, {'account_id': 11880, 'date': '2015-01-15 19:03:38.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 11880, 'date': '2015-01-15 19:05:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

commit_message:
Update volume type name for volume type API

This continues the change for updating volume type to
include changing name.

- Updated the following APIs and tests for volume type

* update volume type
PUT http://<openstackhost>:8776/v2/${tenant_id}/types/${vol_type_id}
body
{
    "volume_type": {
      "name": "test_updated",
      "description":"updated_desc"
    }
}

** user can update name
** if update name, name can not be empty spaces.
** if update name, can not change the name to be the same as the one
in another volume type
** name and description can not be both None

Implements: blueprint volume-type-description
Change-Id: Idc08f796932df709ff20c17f6bc8d4753d85ad3c

[{'created': '2014-08-25 15:36:54.000000000', 'message': 'Integrate OSprofiler and Trove

*) Add osprofiler wsgi middleware
This middleware is used for 2 things:
1) It checks that person who want to trace is trusted and knows
secret HMAC key.
2) It start tracing in case of proper trace headers
and add first wsgi trace point, with info about HTTP request.
*) Add initialization of osprofiler at start of service
Initialize and set an openstack.common.notifier based notifier
instance to osprofiler which be used to send notifications to
Ceilometer. After Trove changed to use olso.messaging (change
Ibd886f3cb4a45250c7c434b3af711abee266671c), will refactoring to
use olso.messaging based osprofiler built-in notifier instead.
*) Use profile enabled context in services interaction
Change service API to pass profile context in, rpc server will
use trace info to initialize their profile context to continue
the profiling for the request as a transaction. The callee could
use continually trace info which server returned as well.
*) Add tracing on service manager and sqlalchemy db driver object

NOTE to test this:
You should put to localrc:
  RECLONE=no
  CEILOMETER_NOTIFICATION_TOPICS=notifications,profiler
  ENABLED_SERVICES+=,ceilometer-acompute,ceilometer-acentral
  ENABLED_SERVICES+=,ceilometer-anotification,ceilometer-collector
  ENABLED_SERVICES+=,ceilometer-alarm-evaluator,ceilometer-alarm-notifier
  ENABLED_SERVICES+=,ceilometer-api
You should use python-pythonclient with this change:
  I5a76e11d428c63d33f6d2c2021426090ebf8340c
Run any command with --profile SECRET_KEY
  $ trove --profile SECRET_KEY create 1
  # it will print <Trace ID>
Get pretty HTML with traces:
  $ osprofiler trace show --html <Profile ID>
note that osprofiler should be run from admin user name & tenant.

Change-Id: I580cce8d2b3c4ec9ce625ac09de6f14e1249f6f5

commit_message:
Integrate OSprofiler and Trove

*) Add osprofiler wsgi middleware
This middleware is used for 2 things:
1) It checks that the person who wants to trace is trusted and knows
the secret HMAC key.
2) It start tracing in case of proper trace headers
and adds the first wsgi trace point, with info about the HTTP request.

*) Add initialization of osprofiler at start of service
Initialize osprofiler with oslo.messaging notifier which
is used to send notifications to Ceilometer.

*) Use profile enabled context in services rpc interaction
Change context serializer to pass profile context to service;
rpc server will use trace info to initialize their profile context
to continue the profiling for the request as a transaction.

*) Add tracing on service manager and sqlalchemy db engine object

NOTE to test this:
You should put to localrc:
  CEILOMETER_NOTIFICATION_TOPICS=notifications,profiler
  ENABLED_SERVICES+=,ceilometer-acompute,ceilometer-acentral
  ENABLED_SERVICES+=,ceilometer-anotification,ceilometer-collector
  ENABLED_SERVICES+=,ceilometer-alarm-evaluator,ceilometer-alarm-notifier
  ENABLED_SERVICES+=,ceilometer-api

Run any command with --profile <SECRET_KEY>
  $ trove --profile <SECRET_KEY> list
  # it will print <Trace ID>
Get pretty HTML with traces:
  $ osprofiler trace show --html <Trace ID>
Note: Trace showing can be executed with the admin account only.

The change to enable Trove exchange in ceilometer has been merged:
Idce1c327c6d21a767c612c13c1ad52a794017d71 .

The change to enable profile in python-troveclient has been merged:
I5a76e11d428c63d33f6d2c2021426090ebf8340c

We prepared a common BP in oslo-spec as the integration change is
similar in all projects: I95dccdc9f274661767d2659c18b96da169891f30
Currently there are 2 other projects are using osprofiler: Glance &
Cinder, and some others are a work in progress.

Change-Id: I580cce8d2b3c4ec9ce625ac09de6f14e1249f6f5
Signed-off-by: Zhi Yan Liu <zhiyanl@cn.ibm.com>

commit_message:
Allow to provide timeout for snapshot generation

removed automatic retries, they can cause duplication of tarballs
even when snapshot can not be generated in given timeout

Change-Id: I4c5fec5d72d2ed76528d1b03d878ca0572e012f2
Closes-Bug: 1414059

[{'created': '2015-03-10 11:23:01.000000000', 'message': 'Set backend_alg for swift_proxy to source

This is a backport of 94ba3bc and 51abd0b from master to juno branch.
Commit 94ba3bc set HAProxy balance algorithm to "source" for swift-proxy
(required by Tempest which makes a lot of quick successive calls to
swift-proxy and were failing when using the default algorithm of
"leastconn").  Commit 51abd0b went back and cleaned up all the
incorrectly referenced variables (_backend_alg to _balance_alg) as the
change made in 94ba3bc wasn't actually taking effect.

Note that the ansible variable name in master is haproxy_balance_alg
whilst in juno it is hap_balance_alg.

Change-Id: I993e019c06f6d7ea7f77dc741d3d418e78ce2ca9
Closes-Bug: #1428081
Closes-Bug: #1429109
'}]
commit_message:
Set backend_alg for swift_proxy to source

This is a backport of 94ba3bc and 51abd0b from master to juno branch.
Commit 94ba3bc set HAProxy balance algorithm to "source" for swift-proxy
(required by Tempest which makes a lot of quick successive calls to
swift-proxy and were failing when using the default algorithm of
"leastconn").  Commit 51abd0b went back and cleaned up all the
incorrectly referenced variables (_backend_alg to _balance_alg) as the
change made in 94ba3bc wasn't actually taking effect.

Note that the ansible variable name in master is haproxy_balance_alg
whilst in juno it is hap_balance_alg.

Change-Id: I993e019c06f6d7ea7f77dc741d3d418e78ce2ca9
Closes-Bug: #1428081
Closes-Bug: #1429109

commit_message:
[IBP] fix apt sources and pinning for fuel-image

Now it could deal with space separated multiple entities in "section"
provided in "repos".

Eg.:
    "repos": [
        {
            "name": "ubuntu",
            "priority": 1001,
            "section": "main restricted universe multiverse",
            "suite": "trusty",
            "type": "deb",
            "uri": "http://archive.ubuntu.com/ubuntu/"
        },
     ]

Partially implements: blueprint ibp-build-ubuntu-images

Change-Id: I7c85de2df4e3e35a0b62b96692b7303254215e48

commit_message:
Use olso.config generator

Stop using the custom script to generate the sample configuration file
and use the oslo-config-generator function of oslo.config.

The change modified "genconfigs" function as a tox testenv (-egenconfigs),
to depend the on oslo-config-generator function of oslo.config.

<This is a modification of Lucas approach to test other possible approach
without including the whole lists of files with config files in
the opts.py file>

Missing: oslo log options until the release of the oslo.log library

Closes-Bug: #1384318

Change-Id: If09fc2b1a82527349fa238f00259856baca6371c
Co-Authored-By: Ghe Rivero <ghe.rivero@hp.com>

commit_message:
Add common code to matchers

Several projects use the same matchers for dicts and XML files,
leading to code duplication. So far, this is included in
nova, keystone, ironic and trove projects.

This is the nova matchers file with pep8 clean and py33 fixes.
Other projects matchers, are just a copy (with minimal
divergences) or a subset of this one.

Change-Id: I915a74aa1b75367d3992819fb17b2f0d5d2a3eae
Partial-Bug: #1199536

commit_message:
Add commands to operate snapshot config

Added two commands to dump snapshot config
and provide it for snapshot task

Will download default config and dump it to stdout

fuel snapshot --conf > conf.yaml

Next command will accept config as input and bypass it to snapshot
generation request

fuel snapshot < conf.yaml

This is required to overwrite certain parameters if needed,
some of those are:
- target directory of snapshot generation
- timeout of snapshot generation procedure
- exclusion/inclusion of certain directories

Depends on I5e01a7459cefe49a128192d82dd827f02866f909
Related-Bug: 1382511
Related-Bug: 1420054
DocImpact

Change-Id: I1ddab26fba1346dad30955289e7d28f4d3aa1562

commit_message:
Make resource creation fail when no 'id' in manifest

This patch makes resource pod/rc/service creation
return 400 status when 'id' field is not passed in
manifest.

Change-Id: I1fa141b9be31788f7956c5b428d7591bc44623dd
Closes-bug: #1430685

commit_message:
Add catch FlavorExtraSpecsNotFound in V2 API.

we catch FlavorExtraSpecsNotFound in v3 API but we didn't catch it
at v2 API. This patch adds it and no need to add unit test
because v2 v3 share unit test.

commit_message:
Stop using RPC namespace to unbreak rolling upgrades

This is a temporary patch until we get an Oslo messaging
release that supports Targets with multiple namespaces:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/163673/

Change-Id: I96e01c00991a9d8602ebc89dbad5206b805c67eb
Related-Bug: #1430984

commit_message:
Set up ssh_known_host based on hostname

Tempest live migration tests use hostnames and resize uses IP addresses,
so set up ssh_known_hosts for both.

Change-Id: Ia647275fa064335277942ef6ac95e2d4ada87a09

commit_message:
Change the engine-listener topic

In oslo.messaging to identify a "rpc server" we have to set the
server attribut of the target. But currently, the engine-listener uses
the hostname of the host, that make all workers on the host to be
identified has same "rpc server" by oslo.messaging, by chance because
heat uses a different topics for each workers, that works.

This change uses the engine id instead of the hostname to identify the
"rpc server" and use the same topic for all engine listeners.

Related-bug: #1414674

Conflicts:
	heat/engine/service.py

Change-Id: I359709ab15ee24ac2459826264adf2373dbb067f
(cherry-picked from commit 9b27efc910695d1be92f2c293d5d11e35e9637f3)

commit_message:
Avoid unnecessarily checking the existence of a device

Plugging a device usually involves checking for the existence of the
device twice, once before calling plug and once after.  It turns out
that these calls are expensive, often taking a half second or more
each.  For that reason, it is worth the effort to make sure we check
only once.

The device driver is now responsible for cleanly plugging/unplugging
the device without knowing whether it exists or not.  Pushing this
responsibility to the device driver allows implementing it more
efficiently in terms of calls made out to the operating system.

This is targetted at the neutron-tempest-parallel bp because it shaves
time off the time to set up a router, something that hinders parallel
performance.

Change-Id: I391fafe68b76e1c620d2b25e8613ba507fd25dfd
Partial-Bug: #1287824

I think about this issue for a bit more, would like share a few thoughts: 1) not only create new volume suffer from same issue, actually any operations that involve scheduler have same problem: e.g. retype, migrate, import volume, create consistency group (although these are admin-only APIs, which should have smaller impact than create volume). So we need a more generic solution; 2) current fix would retry schedule create volume until scheduler_delay <=0, even if a create request can't be satisfied by all backends (i.e. using wrong type, or backend is out of capacity).  We may avoid retrying if scheduler is slightly altered to provide more information (https://review.openstack.org/#/c/162050/ - Raise NoValidHostNotComplete when not all active backends seen on DB have reported stats).

Given these concerns, I'd continue the discussion.  For starter, personally, I prefer moving the sleep&retry OUTSIDE of taskflow in that it's able to apply similar fix to operations that hasn't been moved to taskflow."}, {'account_id': 11600, 'date': '2015-03-10 14:00:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

Thanks for your comments Huang.

1. I agree with you. The problem is create_volume _is_ different. It is using TaskFlow. If we want to have the retry logic in manager then we will be doing unnecessary operations like unpacking the request spec again, because whole flow would need to be started again. For the rest of the operations there already is a generic solution. It is the use of utils.retry decorator (which I'm using internally in create_volume flow). Also if we wanted to retry whole flow then TaskFlow has it's own mechanism for that (http://docs.openstack.org/developer/taskflow/atoms.html#retry) so solution wouldn't be generic for non-TaskFlow operations.
2. I see the point, but wonder if we're able to make FilterScheduler raise NoValidHostNotComplete in a clean way. I guess your PoC is aiming at that and I'm looking forward to see it completed.

I'll post dependent PoC of moving retries out of TaskFlow. It isn't however my preferred way of doing it as I stated in point 1."}, {'account_id': 11600, 'date': '2015-03-10 14:17:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

I was trying to create the PoC of moving retries outside of TaskFlow but I've failed on erroring out the volume (https://github.com/openstack/cinder/blob/master/cinder/scheduler/flows/create_volume.py#L135). To do it properly it would require me to move error notification and erroring out the volume back to the manager and I think this is a very bad idea."}, {'account_id': 11600, 'date': '2015-03-10 19:29:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

commit_message:
Retry requests in scheduler to wait for metrics

This patch adds an interval equal to periodic_interval before
scheduling a volume if request was received between scheduler
service startup and periodic tasks interval. During this time calls to
scheduler_driver are retried till a successful one is resumed or
delay passes. This is to prevent from failing requests received in
that time window due to lack of volume stats.

I also made changes to test_pure to get rid of global monkey patching
of utils.retry decorator which caused problems with writing tests to
this patch.

Change-Id: Iadc6c3a316c7bf3d4f9fd074d76e290b45eae334
Closes-Bug: 1409012

commit_message:
Use the command *ip netns pids* in Neutron OCF scripts

Use command *ip netns pids* instead of lsof. This decreases the time of
getting pids inside namespace. Profit >20 times faster then with lsof.

Change-Id: Ife3f5da3558bf4b5ddd0abbe997cd4b845a8d53c
Closes-bug: #1405477

commit_message:
Memcached task

Configures memcached in a separate task.

CI disabled because it also needs rabbitmq task.

Fuel-CI: disable
Change-Id: I3984e3d8deea7fe977e3778cd142d6fbb3f91f00
Related-Blueprint: fuel-library-modularization

commit_message:
Database, Keystone, Glance tasks

* Install and configure MySQL RDBMS
* Add wait for haproxy backend resource
* Add common ruby tests library

CI disabled because it requires memcached and rabbitmq tasks.

Related blueprint: fuel-library-modularization
Fuel-CI: disable

Change-Id: Ic851bb3e6b8301e13ca5c304d7884eff22fdff2e

Remove obsolete compatibility for Icehouse

Backward compatibility for Icehouse broke Sahara installing,
because of incorrect version condition.

Change-Id: I95d0210445892670ad5d0aa09299dcd41cc14084
Closes-bug: #1430702

commit_message:
New tasks for Horizon, API-proxy and Ceph radosgw

* move Horizon, API proxy and radosgw setup from
  openstack::controller to separate tasks
* minor refactoring of some ceph manifests to allow separate
  ceph::radosgw declaration
* fixing mistake in osnailyfacter::apache_api_proxy - we pass
  master_ip as parameter, so there's no need to pull it via hiera
  inside the class
* fixing warning from api_proxy.conf.erb template

Change-Id: I03810ed51ae015ac64dde6e82ce2f721a42f45d3
Related-Blueprint: fuel-library-modularization

commit_message:
add cadf notifications for oauth

Adds support for cadf notifications for create/update/delete of
consumers, request tokens and access tokens.

Change-Id: Iaa8e148cde3af881c8b573ab9d27bf366134c865

subject: Add scope info to initiator data for CADF notifications

commit_message:
Add scope info to initiator data for CADF notifications

the project id (or domain id) is important information to audit,
as such, it should be added to the initiator block of a CADF
notification.

Change-Id: I7d73f671130485e449820d7f6d38a25c3bbc05bf
Closes-Bug: 1428945
